# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albert-chevallier-tayler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] He is most known for his twelve-year involvement with the Newlyn School of painting.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] The Newlyn School was spawned after many international artists followed the En plein air school in France, whereby artists would leave Paris and take up rural life in small colonies of kindred painters.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] Thence, as artists returned from France to their own countries, they sought out remote locations to congregate and pursue the En plein air method.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] The Newlyn School is also known as British Impressionism.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] A typical painting of this early period is *A Dress Rehearsal* (1888), hung in the National Museums Liverpool.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] This painting makes use of light and shadow and is based upon a genre scene as might have occurred in Cornwall.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] The Newlyn School drew their subjects from everyday life in the local area.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] Other associate artists of the Newlyn School were Henry Scott Tuke, Thomas Cooper Gotch, Caroline Gotch, Stanhope Forbes, Leghe Suthers, Walter Langley and Elizabeth Armstrong.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] On arrival in Newlyn, he lived in lodgings in Henry & Elizabeth Maddern's Belle Vue House with Forbes and Blandford Fletcher.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] During the 1890s he maintained connections with the art centre of London and exhibited regularly at the Royal Academy; however, at about the turn of the century he moved to London and converted to a more genteel, urban lifestyle.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] Tayler began painting more grand scenes of the cities of Europe.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] In 1901 he painted one of his largest and most masterful works, *The Ceremony of the Garter*, depicting the famous late Middle Ages scene at Eltham Palace in which the fallen garter of Joan of Kent is picked up by King Edward III.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] This event circa 1348 led to Edward III founding the Order of the Garter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] Tayler was an avid cricketer, and in 1905 produced a set of twelve watercolours of famous and mostly royal cricket players.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] Lord Leverhulme used the series to produce lithographs and advertise his Lever Brothers soap products.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] The promotion proved popular, and the National Portrait Gallery, London has nine of these images hanging.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] In 1906 he painted a famous picture of a cricket match in progress, *Kent vs Lancashire at Canterbury*, which was commissioned by Kent.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/albert-chevallier-tayler] In June 2006, the county sold the painting at auction for £680,000, a record price for a cricket painting.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The website has gone through several branding changes since it was launched.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Originally named BBC Online, it was rebranded as BBCi (which itself was the brand name for interactive TV services) before being named *bbc.co.uk*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It was then renamed BBC Online again in 2008, although the service uses the branding "BBC".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 26 February 2010 *The Times* claimed that Mark Thompson, then Director General of the BBC, proposed that the BBC's web output should be cut by 50%, with online staff numbers and budgets reduced by 25% in a bid to scale back BBC operations and allow commercial rivals more room.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 2 March 2010, the BBC reported that it would cut its website spending by 25% and close BBC 6 Music and Asian Network.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 24 January 2011, the confirmed cuts of 25% were announced, leaving a £34 million shortfall.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This resulted in the closure of several sites, including BBC Switch, BBC Blast, 6-0-6, and the announcement of plans to sell the Douglas Adams created site h2g2.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Within 12 months, the BBC website offered "Auntie" online discussion groups; web pages for select web-related programs and BBC departments; free web pages for associate members.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC Multimedia Centre was a team led by Martin Freeth to introduce new media across the corporation.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Networking Club ***www.bbcnc.org.uk*** (the "nc" standing for "networking club") was launched by BBC Education on 11 May 1994 as a non-profit paid subscription service.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] For a joining fee of £25 and a monthly subscription of £12, members of the club were given access to an early type of social networking site featuring a bulletin board for sharing information and real-time conversation, along with a dialup Internet connection service.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC Director General John Birt sought government approval to direct licence fee revenue into the service, describing planned BBC Internet services as the "third medium" joining the BBC's existing TV and radio networks, achieving a change in the BBC Charter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This led to the official launch of *BBC Online* at the *www.bbc.co.uk* address in April 1997.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] As well as the licence fee funded www.bbc.co.uk, BBC Worldwide launched the commercially funded beeb.com, featuring mostly entertainment focused content, with sites including *Radio Times*, *Top Gear* and *Top of the Pops*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Later, BBC Online launched licence-fee funded web sites for *Top of the Pops* and *Top Gear*, resulting in some duplication.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Beeb.com was later refocussed as an online shopping guide, and was closed in 2002. beeb.com later redirected to the BBC Shop website, run by BBC Worldwide.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In 1999, the BBC bought the **bbc.com** domain name, previously owned by Boston Business Computing, for $375,000, but the price of this purchase was not revealed until six years later.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] As of 2005, *www.bbcnc.org.uk* no longer exists.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In 2001, BBC Online was rebranded as BBCi; the website launched on 7 November 2001.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBCi name was conceived as an umbrella brand for all the BBC's digital interactive services across web, digital teletext, interactive TV and on mobile platforms.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The use of letter "i" prefixes and suffixes to denote information technology or interactivity was very much in vogue at this time; according to the BBC, the "i" in BBCi stood for "interactivity" as well as "innovation".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] As part of the rebrand, BBC website pages all displayed a standard navigation bar across the top of the screen, offering category-based navigation: Categories, TV, Radio, Communicate, Where I Live, A-Z Index and a search function.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The navbar was designed to offer a similar navigation system to the i-bar on BBCi interactive television.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] After three years of consistent use across different platforms, the BBC began to drop the BBCi brand gradually; on 6 May 2004, the BBC website was renamed bbc.co.uk, after the main URL used to access the site.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Interactive TV services continued under the BBCi brand until it was dropped completely in 2008.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC's online video player, the iPlayer has, however, retained an i-prefix in its branding.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 14 December 2007, a beta version of a new bbc.co.uk homepage was launched, with the ability to customise the page by adding, removing and rearranging different categories, such as 'News', 'Weather' and 'Entertainment'.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The widget-based design was inspired by sites such as Facebook and iGoogle, and allowed the BBC to add new content to the homepage while still retaining users' customisations.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The new homepage also incorporated the clock design used in the 1970s on the BBC's television service into the large header and a box containing featured content of the website.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The new BBC homepage left beta on Wednesday, 27 February 2008 to serve as the new BBC Homepage under the same URL as the previous version.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 30 January 2010, a new webpage design became available as a beta version, that by May 2010, replaced the old homepage.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This homepage expanded on the modules idea and the customisation theme.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The website allowed certain themes that interested the viewer to be tracked, via a new module.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It also included a new 'Media Zone' where featured content could be displayed, with this new featured box being located across the entire top of the webpage, below the header.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The Media Zone was also changed so that the content changed by running the mouse over the tabs.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The header was again changed to include the headings of the major sections of the website, these being: Home, News, Sport, Weather, iPlayer, TV, Radio and more, spread out evenly across the header.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This new header was included across the entire website.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Despite the cosmetic appearance of the relaunch, the new website was actually relaunched using a completely different operating system, allowing the site's four different international versions to be more easily altered.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It also brought their website layouts and operations closer to that of the main website.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This new style of header included the headings as before, but with the search box redesigned and aligned right, as with the links which are significantly smaller.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Other links, such as BBC id login and mobile versions of the website also appear on the header, just to the right of the smaller BBC logo.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 21 September 2011, a new BBC homepage went into beta testing that was drastically different from those before it.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The new homepage was based on feedback that stated that the current page was too narrow in focus and not distinctive enough, with the homepage not displaying the full extend of the BBC Online site and that some did not realise it was the homepage.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] As a result, they launched a new version that featured as a centrepiece a revolving carousel of content on the BBC Online website, with filters beneath to restrict it to, and to show more of entertainment, lifestyle, knowledge and news and sports topics.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] At the top of the page, a new header has been inserted giving the date, the time through the use of the vintage BBC clock, as well as weather prospects for the next three days through the use of the traditional weather symbols.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Below the carousel, boxes contain links to the most popular video material, web articles and pages on the site, as well as TV and Radio listings alongside an A-Z list of the BBC's top level domains.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This new site replaced the previous one on 30 November 2011.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In a blog post from the same day, James Thornett explained the changes – while the post attracted complaints from users disliking the refreshed layout, the new-look site was critically acclaimed and nominated by the Design Museum as one of their Designs of the Year in 2012.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Online contains a variety of content ranging from News, Sport, Music, Science, Technology and Entertainment, amongst other things.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The website has a British orientation, although the home page, news section and sports section each provide different content between UK and "International" visitors.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] There are also separate pages for Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland written by the BBC Nations.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The website focuses around the primary top level domains of News, Sport, Weather, iPlayer, TV and Radio.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] These are easily accessible from the taskbar running across the top of all current BBC Online pages.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] However, other top level domains are also in existence: some are available from a drop down list on the taskbar including CBBC, CBeebies, Comedy, Food, Health, History, Learning, Music, Science and Nature, while other top level domains are only available through the A-Z index on the BBC website.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] These include Archives, Arts & Culture, Ethics, Gardening, Parenting, Religion and Travel news.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] However, there are many more top level domains – some 400 in March 2010 however this number has decreased as top level domains now frequently link to a lower domain name – that link to websites for individual services or programmes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] One of the most used aspects of the BBC Online website are the sections relating to News content, Sports results and news and Weather forecasts.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The **BBC News Online** subsite launched in 1997 and received around 2 billion page views each month in 2012.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The site contains journalistic content from the BBC covering news from the UK, both as a whole as well as regional news from the BBC Nations and Regions, and International content.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The site also contains analysis from correspondents and other features from the Magazine section of the website.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The **BBC Sport Online** subsite offers, in a similar way to news, a wide variety of material including sports results, live feeds to on-air programming, sports related news and analysis from commentators and pundits.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The **BBC iPlayer** subsite allows programmes to be viewed again after broadcast over the Internet.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This successful site has now been expanded to include mobile views and downloads onto computers and mobiles allowing viewing for up to 30 days after broadcast.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Programmes is available as HTML and RDF/XML and JSON.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC Programme Catalogue is an internal archive of the BBC back catalogue which was briefly available online to the public in beta.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC also operates numerous sub sites that focus on different topics and subjects to expand the knowledge of the reader.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] These are mainly centred around the topics of Science, Nature, Arts and Culture, Religion and Ethics, Food and History.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Each of these sub sites feature new articles published on the topic and contain other collections relating to the topic.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] For example, the **Food** site contains recipes featured on various BBC cookery programmes, the **History** site has an interactive timeline of key events and individuals, the **Nature** site contains a database of creatures, and the **Language** site teaches phrases and more in 40 languages.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Included in this range was the well received Your Paintings website that catalogued every painting in public ownership for view.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Until 2013, the BBC also hosted a **health** website with detailed information, checked by professionals, of medical conditions and symptoms.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] However, the BBC withdrew the site as this service is available from other sources on the Internet which did not exist when the Health site launched, the most prominent of which is NHS Choices.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In addition to these subsites, the BBC also runs sites dedicated to education and learning.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] These include the Bitesize revision website for teenagers and a section with resources for teachers including Learning Zone Class Clips that provides video from educational programmes for use in the classroom.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC plans to merge this content into one easier to access site in the foreseeable future.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Own It is an offshoot that provides online safety advice for parents, teachers, and young people to help them make positive choices online.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It follows in the footsteps of other online safety services such as Internet Matters and Childnet.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC runs a comprehensive children's website.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It includes information on all of CBBC's shows along with several subsites covering art, sport, news, and other current events.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Its message boards are especially popular with children who use them to communicate with each other about all of CBBC's output among other salient topics for kids like bullying, books, and personal problems.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In conjunction with the Children's subsite, the BBC also runs an online revision website using the Bitesize brand and also ran a message board for students.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This latter service, now called "BBC Student Life" and previously called "Onion Street", was launched in 2001 and is aimed at young people between the ages of 11 and 16.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The site offers a pre-moderated forum discussion on school work, revision and other areas of learning.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC previously ran a page to help young people sort out their life difficulties entitled "Your Life".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The page featured agony uncle "Ask Aaron", a professional psychotherapist who provided regular answers to children's questions across the message boards; after the page's closure, the agony uncle has moved on to Radio One's Sunday Surgery as their mental health expert.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] There is integration between television output and website content with aspects of children's programming have follow-up information on their websites.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] An international BBC subsite named "BBC Britain" is only available to users with IP addresses outside the UK.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] No money from the licence fee was used to create this website.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Blast was the BBC's network which encouraged teenagers to become creative in music, film, dance, art and fashion.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It provided access to mentors online, and at free events and workshops across the UK.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The website specifically catered for 13- to 19-year-olds but the BBC Blast project also ran a variety of work experience schemes for young adults between the ages of 18 and 25.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It included an online forum where participants could upload videos, audio tracks and images and comment on each other's work.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] There was an annual season on BBC2 where their films could be shown.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC Blast tour built partnerships with local arts organisations around the UK, featuring workshops and talks with stars from a variety of backgrounds, and providing a performance space for participants.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] These including rapper Akala, director and actor Noel Clarke, the artists Antony Gormley and Jake and Dinos Chapman, BBC Radio 1Xtra DJs Ace and Vis, singer-songwriter Jay Sean, rapper Chipmunk, Panjabi Hit Squad and Yngve & The Innocent.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The tour also featured very early performances and interviews by artists such as Rizzle Kicks and Ed Sheeran.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Blast worked with a number of national partners to put on events and give teenagers' content a chance to be used at a higher level.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] These included the Victoria and Albert Museum, RSC, National Portrait Gallery, National Theatre, Zoo Nation, and the British Film Institute.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 24 January 2011, the BBC announced the closure of BBC Blast as part of a 25% cut to the BBC Online budget, resulting in a £34 million shortfall.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] From 1999 to 2005, the BBC ran a popular subsite called *Cult TV*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] This subsite had news, star interviews, trivia, and other content popular with fans of the cult TV shows they covered.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Examples of covered TV shows include *The X-Files*, *Doctor Who*, *Buffy the Vampire Slayer*, *Farscape* and *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 15 July 2005, the BBC announced that the site was closing as of the end of the month, although the *Doctor Who* section would be unaffected as the series was an ongoing BBC concern.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The announcement explained that this was "part of the restructuring of the BBC's online activities".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It was promised that some of the content would be moved to new places on bbc.co.uk, although as of January 2017 it is currently still all online at the no-longer-updated Cult site.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In recent years, some of the content covered in the Cult section was included in the BBC's Archive section, such as content and information on the 25th Anniversary of Children's BBC.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The *BBC Guide to Comedy* was an online encyclopaedia based on Mark Lewisohn's 1998 book *The Radio Times Guide to Comedy*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It offered "Info on every TV comedy shown in the UK, from 1936 to today..." and featured articles on almost every comedy programme and sitcom produced by the main channels in the United Kingdom.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The site also featured video clips, viewable in RealPlayer, and a small gallery of cast photographs or screenshots.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] It was replaced by a smaller, less detailed guide in 2007, which only focussed on BBC shows and is also now discontinued.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Democracy Live was a subsite of the BBC that contains live streams and recorded programmes from deciding bodies that affect the UK.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Launched in November 2009, the site focused around live and recorded debate from the House of Commons and the House of Lords in Westminster, the Scottish Parliament, the National Assembly for Wales, the Northern Ireland Assembly and the European Parliament.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] While recordings tended to focus on the main debating chambers, the site also hosted video from some committees.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The site also included a search facility to find relevant debate, a tool to follow a particular member and see videos of their contributions and other videos of historic events from these institutions.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The service also allowed the translation of Welsh Assembly proceedings to and from Welsh.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Most of its services are now covered by the Freeview/BBC iPlayer channels BBC Parliament and its website (bbc.co.uk/tv/bbcparliament).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC's site was initially entirely free from advertising; this was due to the BBC's funding being derived primarily from compulsory television licence fees from UK viewers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Studios who exploit BBC brands commercially have had several attempts at launching services online including Beeb.com in the late 1990s.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In 2006, the BBC began making controversial plans to raise revenue by including advertising on the international version of BBC News Online accessed from outside the United Kingdom.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Online is currently freely available worldwide (via various URLs including bbc.com/news) but planned video services and a lower than expected licence fee settlement paid for by UK residents only led to the BBC introducing banner advertisements to the site from November 2007.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC Trust approved the plans for introducing advertisements which also involved creating bbc.com as a part of BBC Worldwide.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Sir Michael Lyons, Chairman of the Trust, confirmed the BBC would not charge for online news following News International's planned introduction of charges for online content.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Prior to this there had been criticism from some, as web users outside the UK could use the services (including the entire BBC radio services) without having to pay for them.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In addition, where rights to sporting events (such as certain football or cricket matches) do not include international online coverage, users from outside the UK are blocked from listening to commentaries.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] On 24 January 2011, it was announced that the BBC was to cut its online budget by 25% or £34 million.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] To cope with this, many BBC websites would be closed including BBC Switch, BBC Blast, 6-0-6, BBC raw, Video Nation, and planned to sell the Douglas Adams created website h2g2, as well as the automation of many programme websites and radio websites.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] A service, called BBC iPlayer, was launched in December 2007, which allows users to download both radio and TV content for up to seven days after broadcast.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The television version allows users to either stream programmes or to download them using peer-to-peer and DRM technology.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Initially streams were generally broadcast in the RealAudio and RealVideo formats controlled by RealNetworks and the BBC drew criticism with some for using those closed formats which, at the time, could only be played using RealPlayer.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In response to such criticisms, the BBC negotiated a deal with RealNetworks a 'cut-down' version of RealPlayer which did not contain as much advertising and marketing.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Windows Media has also been adopted and since Autumn 2006, a Windows Media stream of all national BBC radio stations has been available.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] More recently, the BBC has been experimenting with MP3 downloads and podcasting facilities for an increasing number of radio shows, with a high level of success; a less publicised trial of Ogg Vorbis streams for certain programmes was less successful, and has now been discontinued.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] During major events, the BBC often features liveblogs which publish the most recent text and image posts from BBC correspondents; particularly significant political events may pair live blogs with live video streams or recorded video loops relevant to the event.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In February 2001, BBC Online incorporated Douglas Adams' previously independent h2g2 project into its group of web sites, and eventually replaced all its existing message boards, which used an archaic system called Howerd, with the DNA software derived from that project.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The site's now archived *Collective* magazine also used the DNA software along with numerous other sites created after the BBC's acquisition of h2g2.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The website has extensive technical information available about its operation.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The BBC also made some of the content on bbc.co.uk and the BBC News Website available in XML format on the former developer network backstage.bbc.co.uk.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Also, through participation in the Creative Archive Licence group, bbc.co.uk allows legal downloads of selected material via the Internet.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In November 2011, the BBC launched the Connected Studio initiative which resulted in the running of workshops for independent web designers to work with the BBC in conceiving new designs and ways for current BBC services to be improved.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] BBC Online uses several third-party companies to log information from users, by means of cookies.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In March 2007, a vulnerability was exposed in the BBC's "Most Emailed" and "Most Read" news sections which could allow for the popularity of a news article to be exaggerated and thus highlight it to other website visitors.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In early 2004, the site was made the focus of a government review, launched by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, led by Philip Graf.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] Sections of the UK Internet industry had argued that the BBC site offered things that were available in the commercial sector, creating unnecessary competition.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The review was published in July 2004 and it was recommended that the BBC "prioritise news, current affairs, education and information which is of value to the citizen." In response the BBC also shut down a small number of sections of the site, including the Soaps section.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] In November 2004, the Governors of the BBC announced a newer, much more tightly drawn remit for bbc.co.uk as part of their response to the review.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] They also announced, as Graf had recommended, a new approach towards external providers which will see bbc.co.uk aiming to spend at least 25% of its eligible budget on content and services through independent commissions by the end of 2006/07.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bbc-co-uk] The implementation of the Graf report has seen the popular message boards in the BBC Sport section shut down, as the BBC tries to promote its 606 brand, but these changes have proved unpopular as the interface has proven unusable and large numbers of content providers have abandoned the BBC site.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] Fletcher was born in London in 1858 to William Fletcher, a linen draper and upholsterer, and his wife Eliza (née Bartholomew).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] Against his father's wishes, Fletcher studied art at the South Kensington School of Art from the age of 16 to 20, winning the Silver Medal and the Queen's Prize.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] During that time he visited Brittany, making acquaintance with Stanhope Forbes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] Fletcher joined the life class at Charles Verlat's Academie Royale in Antwerp, where he became friends with Frank Bramley, Fred Hall and Walter Osborne.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] He spent time painting at Pont-Aven and Dinan in France, during which time he became friends with Frederick Millard and met Jules Bastien-Lepage.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] In the 1884 Royal Academy shows he exhibited four paintings executed at Pont-Aven and Quimperlé, although he did not become a Royal Academician.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] He was an early member of the Newlyn School in 1885, where he worked on a single large canvas, *Dame Grigson's Academy*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] Fletcher lived in lodgings in Henry & Elizabeth Maddern's Belle Vue House with Forbes and Albert Chevallier Tayler.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] The same year he permanently left the artists' colony.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] He travelled, sometimes with Osborne, and continued to travel and worked as a wandering artist until settling in Dorking in 1904 and then Abingdon-on-Thames in 1915.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] Fletcher's most famous work is *Evicted* (painted in Steventon in 1887), which was the first painting acquired by the Queensland Art Gallery in 1896.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] It was bought for a sum reported variously to be 300, 400 or 450 guineas.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] *Under Petticoat Government* (1891) was initially also acquired by QAG in 1896 on a loan arrangement.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] In 1942 *Evicted* inspired the 11-year-old Betty Churcher to decide to be an artist.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] "Looking at those boots and the wonder of those autumn leaves on the road brought it all back in a rush.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] In 1900, 1907, 1909 and 1938 it was one of a number of paintings sent on tours of Queensland country towns.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] Campbell called for it to be "discarded", and declared that "[it] is not Art", further stating that it was a mere "illustration".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] John Cooper, director of the Moreton Galleries in Brisbane, stated that it should be auctioned off, notwithstanding that it was QAG's most popular picture.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] It formed part of an exhibition of request paintings at QAG in 1954.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] Engaged since 1888, Fletcher married Norah Beatrice Emmeline Harris (1863-1960) in 1894.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/blandford-fletcher] They had two daughters, one of whom was the sculptor Rosamund Fletcher.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school is affiliated with Woodard Schools, as only the governors/governing body is fully responsible for the school's performance, but hold responsibility to the Woodard Board.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] On Woodard Schools website it is listed under "Woodard Incorporated Schools (independent)".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Founded as a school of the Oxford Movement, Bloxham is a member of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The original school on the site in the north of the village of Bloxham was founded in 1853 by John William Hewett (1824–1886), a local Anglo-Catholic curate.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school was supported by Samuel Wilberforce, who commissioned the diocesan architect, George Edmund Street, to draw up plans for the new school buildings.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Street's design was described by *The Gentleman's Magazine* as the 'most beautiful modern Gothic buildings ever devoted in England to a scholastic purpose'.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The foundation stone was blessed by Wilberforce on 7 June 1855.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Hewett's plans were for a school for 100 commoners, 40 scholars and an unspecified number of choristers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] In February 1855, a trust for the school was established, naming it **All Saints' Grammar School**, with the intent of providing for 'the liberal education of the sons of the clergy, gentry, Naval, Military and professional men and others'.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Hewett contributed his extensive library and the bulk of the funds for the ambitious building project.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] By mid-1856, Hewett was bankrupt, and the school had failed to attract sufficient numbers of boys, who were expected to pay unusually high fees.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Hewett's school, with several dozen pupils and incomplete buildings, was closed in April 1857.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school trust approached Nathaniel Woodard for help, but he was uninterested in buying or supporting the school.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] In 1859, Hewett's dilapidated school buildings were bought for £1,615 by Philip Reginald Egerton, a Church of England curate working in Deddington.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Like Hewett, he was strongly influenced by the Oxford Movement and sought to establish a new school to teach its values.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Egerton adopted the previous foundation's name of **All Saints' School**, and its motto, but based the school's ethos on that of his alma mater, Winchester College.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] He sought the backing of several notable academics and clergymen, including Wilberforce, Woodard and Henry Liddon.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The project was initially funded by Egerton's wealthy wife, Harriet, and received its first pupil on 31 January 1860.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Under the personal leadership of Egerton, Bloxham initially provided education for middle-class boys in the public school tradition, although classics was originally not widely taught.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] In 1861 there were 29 pupils and by 1863 there were 60.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Thanks to Wilberforce's continued support, Street drew up new plans for expanding the neo-Gothic school buildings, and additional money was provided by John Hubbard, 1st Baron Addington and John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The new buildings were unveiled in 1864 in the presence of Thomas Parker, 6th Earl of Macclesfield and Benjamin Disraeli.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Chapel Wing, the last of Street's buildings, was opened on 21 February 1873.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school quickly grew, rising to two hundred pupils in twenty years.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Despite Egerton's plans for the school to provide for local farmers and tradesmen, a report in 1870 found that most of the boys were from professional, ecclesiastical and military families.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] An 1879 plan by Egerton and Liddon to affiliate the school with Keble College, Oxford never came to fruition, and Egerton was forced to look elsewhere to ensure the school's long-term viability.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Bloxham School Trust was established in 1884, and in 1897 the school was admitted into the Woodard Corporation.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Frederick Scobell Boissier, father of Harrow headmaster Arthur Boissier, taught at Bloxham from 1878 to 1898 and was headmaster from 1886.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Education at the school focused on the notions of religious and civic duty, and the Anglo-Catholic nature of the foundation of the school remained a defining feature.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Proposals to secularise the school by renaming it 'Bloxham College' were rejected in 1911 and 1951.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham's first headmaster to not be a priest was only appointed in 1925.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] During the 1890s, Bloxham shrank in size as the local provision of state education improved.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Education Act 1902 worsened the situation, as did a growing prejudice against high church practices in schools.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school's impressive academic record and high Oxbridge entrant rates in the 1900s helped it to survive.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] By the 1910s, a prefect system, house rivalries, corporal punishment and fagging confirmed Bloxham's identity as a conforming public school, although the latter two practices were abolished in the 1970s.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Like many public schools, Bloxham suffered disproportionately high casualties during the First World War, in which over 400 current and former pupils served and 79 were killed.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school survived the subsequent economic depression, and embarked upon a series of ambitious educational and building reforms led by the school's first lay headmaster, Valentine Armitage.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] During the 1960s the school pioneered a tutoring system in which boys of multiple year groups shared a tutor.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] This system has since been imitated by many other boarding schools.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Girls started to be admitted into the sixth form in small numbers in the early 1970s and the school became fully co-educational in 1998.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Lower School, for pupils aged 11–13, was opened in 1994.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school achieved 52% 9-7 grades in the 2022 GCSEs.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham School has grounds which cover approximately 60 acres (240,000 m2) in the village of Bloxham.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Neo-Gothic complex of buildings designed by George Edmund Street, called Main School, dominates the school and the north end of the village.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] It contains two boarding houses, Crake and Wilson, the dining hall, the Masters' Dining Room, the Headmaster's office, the chapel, the 1894 Egerton Library and a number of classrooms.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Palmer House, built in 1874 in the Neo-Gothic style, is the school hospital.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Egerton House, on the edge of the school campus, was built in 1876 as the Headmaster's House, and was enlarged in 1886.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school's Great Hall was completed in 1937 and was built in the traditional Cotswold style.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Victorian-era Wesley Theatre, a former Methodist chapel, is the school theatre.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Science Block was built between 1959 and 1966.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Wilberforce House was built in the late 1960s and Raymond House was opened in 1971 by Margaret Thatcher.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Recent building developments include the Raymond Technology Centre, the expansion of the Lower School building and the Vallance Library which was opened by Colin Dexter in April 2006.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] New squash courts have also been built next to the Dewey Sports Centre, and the art school has been increased in size.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The extension to the 1901 music school was completed in the summer of 2007, and officially opened by Aled Jones in November 2008.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The sixth form is located in a modernised building called The White Lion, a former public house on the edge of the school campus.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham has a Church of England chapel which can accommodate approximately two hundred people.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] It was built at first-floor level with classrooms beneath, giving it an elevated position.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] At its west end is a balcony and organ loft, with an octagonal turret containing the bell tower rising above Main School.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] At the east end of the chapel is a *Te Deum* window made by Clayton and Bell in memory of Wilberforce.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The chapel also contains a rood screen, windows in memory of Egerton and the Boer Wars, and monuments to the school's war dead.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The reredos was designed by Bucknall in 1912.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The smaller Liddon Chapel, adjacent to the main chapel, is used as a classroom.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham School has four playing fields, three of which are used for cricket in the summer term.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] It has two AstroTurf all-weather pitches, which are used for hockey and tennis, as well as additional hard tennis courts.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Dewey Sports Centre, opened by Anne, Princess Royal in 1986, has an indoor sports hall, a gym and a climbing wall.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Along with the swimming pool, which was refurbished in 2014, it is available for public use.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Deer Park is where the bursary is situated, as well as some of the buildings used by the CCF, including the armoury and shooting range.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Woollen Hale, the house of Bloxham headmasters since 1986, is on the top of Hobb Hill, overlooking playing fields and the Main School.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Like most traditional public schools, houses form the basis of school organisation and are incorporated into the boarding system.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] There are seven boarding houses within the senior school, as well as one day house (Merton).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The boarding houses are Crake, Egerton, Raymond, Seymour, Stonehill, Wilberforce and Wilson, with Raymond, Stonehill and Wilberforce being the girls' houses.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] There is also a junior boarding house, Park Close, for the first form (Year 7) and second form (Year 8) weekly boarders, but all junior pupils are members of Exham House.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school operates a house-based tutor system, in which pupils of several year groups share a tutor within one house.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] All houses are made up of both boarders and day pupils, who are called 'day boarders'.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] House captains are appointed each year and make up part of the school's prefect body.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The two oldest houses are Crake and Wilson, previously called School House, with all the other houses constituted later.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The newest boarding house to be built was Seymour, which was finished in 1982.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Although Stonehill and Merton, in the current establishment were the last to be constituted but in older buildings than Seymour.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Houses provide a focus for social and sporting activity, with rivalries existing between different houses.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school has hosted the Bloxham Festival of Faith and Literature since October 2011.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school requires all students to visit a chapel service that is held in the school's chapel every week on Wednesday morning, service lasting from 20 to 40 minutes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Students that are partaking in exams or otherwise unable to attend it are only expected to attend the next service.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The services are run by the school's chaplain, and the service style changes with change of chaplain.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] For some events the school is gathered in St Mary's church, as it is impossible to fit the entire school into chapel.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Events that are held in the church are mostly 1st or last service of a term, which coincidentally often fall on religious holidays.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Bloxham Project is an inter-school council started in the 1960s to address the role of religion in schools.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] It was started by the Chairman of Bloxham School Council and the school chaplain, Donald Dowie.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The first Bloxham Conference on Public School Religion took place in 1967 at Bloxham School, and today approximately 120 independent schools take part in the project.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] It is a full-time organisation which continues to promote Christian educational values in the United Kingdom.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The project is currently run from Ripon College Cuddesdon near Oxford, where several of Bloxham's headmasters have been educated.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Sport plays a significant role in Bloxham life, with afternoons on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Saturdays being allocated to games' practices and matches for pupils in years 9–13.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Every pupil in the school is involved in sport, with the aim being that each pupil will represent the school in at least one team during their time at Bloxham.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The major sports are rugby, hockey and cricket for boys, and hockey, netball and tennis for girls.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Other sports played at Bloxham include squash, athletics, swimming, golf, horse riding, polo, target shooting, basketball, clay pigeon shooting, fives, sailing, cross-country and badminton.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham has several societies, some of which are pupil-run.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] School societies include the Scholars Society, the Debating Society and the Common Room Society.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The Choral Society, or Chapel Choir, sing twice a week during the school's chapel services.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Clubs include a Photography Club, a Wildlife Club and a Model Railway Club.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham School was host of the British Youth Go Tournament in 2011.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Pupils can take part in other activities, such as the Duke of Edinburgh Award, drama, community service, dance, adventure training, horse riding and management and horticulture.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham runs a Combined Cadet Force (CCF) for pupils in third form (Year 9) and above.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] This was founded in 1910 as the school's Officers' Training Corps.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Most terms there is a CCF over-night expedition and a range day.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The CCF was formerly affiliated with the Royal Green Jackets and is now affiliated with its successor regiment, The Rifles.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school has a music department which offers professional tuition in brass, guitar, keyboard, organ, percussion, singing, strings and woodwind.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school magazine is called *The Bloxhamist* and is published annually, at the beginning of Michaelmas term.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The school's prefect system was introduced in a form by Armitage in the late 1920s.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Prefects were solemnly initiated in chapel, and once in office they were responsible for much of the daily administration of the school.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Prefects were in charge of most discipline and a prefectural code was introduced; school prefects could give up to six strokes with a cane, and house prefects three.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Currently, prefects only serve symbolic roles: charity prefect, sports prefect, etc and do not have or serve any other duties.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The motto of Bloxham School is taken from Hewitt's 1853 school.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] A quotation from the Book of Proverbs, it is *Justorum Semita Lux Splendens* (Latin), which translates as "The path of the just is a shining light".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Until 2009, the school arms was that of the Egerton family, although this usage was never registered with the College of Arms.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] It is now a stylised version of the original coat-of-arms.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Additional overnight stays for day boarders are charged at £59 a night.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Current members of the school are known as 'Bloxhamists' with alumni referred to as '**Old Bloxhamists'**, or OBs for short.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The stone arch at the main entrance to the school was built to the memory of Bloxham pupils who have died in conflict, and the school chapel contains memorials to the school's war dead from multiple conflicts.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] Bloxham suffered a high casualty rate during World War I, in which 79 current and former pupils were killed.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The portraits of the school's dead of the First World War are hung near the chapel.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The first five headmasters at Bloxham were ordained Anglican priests, with the first lay headmaster being appointed in 1925.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/bloxham-school] The portraits of former headmasters hang in the school dining hall.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] She was the youngest of the three daughters of Edward Yates, a wealthy local property owner.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] She studied at the Heatherley School of Fine Art in 1878 and then at the Slade School of Art in London before enrolling at the Academie Julian in Paris during 1880.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] While at the Slade she met Thomas Cooper Gotch and the couple married in August 1881 at St Peter's Church in Newlyn.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] They returned to France, where their daughter, Phyllis Maureen, was born in September 1882.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] Despite protracted periods of ill-health following child-birth, Gotch and her husband travelled extensively including an 1883 trip to Australia.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] They lived in London between 1884 and 1887 before settling in Newlyn where they eventually built a family home, Wheal Betsy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] In Newlyn the couple were founding members of the St Ives Art Club and active in the artists' groups then being established in the area.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] Caroline Gotch exhibited regularly at the Royal Academy between 1887 and 1895 and with the Royal Society of British Artists throughout the 1880s.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] Gotch showed at the Paris Salon in 1897 and 1898 where she was awarded second and third place medals.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] She showed works at the Royal Hibernian Academy in 1879, at the New English Art Club in 1888, at the Society of Women Artists in 1879 and 1893 and also with the Royal Glasgow Institute of the Fine Arts between 1886 and 1894.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] In both 1895 and 1896, she had pieces shown at the Glass Palace in Munich.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] Gotch also showed at commercial galleries, including the Grosvenor Gallery, the Goupil Gallery and the Fine Art Society.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/caroline-gotch] Despite her exhibition record, very few examples of Gotch's work survive but photographs show sophisticated compositions, often featuring women and children in domestic settings.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The fielding team aims to prevent runs by dismissing batters (so they are "out").
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] When ten batters have been dismissed, the innings (playing phase) ends and the teams swap roles.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Traditionally, cricketers play in all-white kit, but in limited overs cricket, they wear club or team colours.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In addition to the basic kit, some players wear protective gear to prevent injury caused by the ball, which is a hard, solid spheroid made of compressed leather with a slightly raised sewn seam enclosing a cork core layered with tightly wound string.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The earliest known definite reference to cricket is to it being played in South East England in the mid-16th century.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] It spread globally with the expansion of the British Empire, with the first international matches in the second half of the 19th century.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The game's governing body is the International Cricket Council (ICC), which has over 100 members, twelve of which are full members who play Test matches.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The game's rules, the *Laws of Cricket*, are maintained by the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) in London.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The sport is primarily played in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Afghanistan, Australia, New Zealand, England and Wales, South Africa and the West Indies.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] While cricket has traditionally been played largely by men, women's cricket has experienced significant growth in the 21st century.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The most successful side playing international cricket is Australia, which has won eight One Day International trophies, including six World Cups, more than any other country, and has been the top-rated Test side more than any other country.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Cricket is one of many games in the "club ball" sphere that involve hitting a ball with a hand-held implement.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Others include baseball (which shares many similarities with cricket, both belonging in the more specific bat-and-ball games category), golf, hockey, tennis, squash, badminton and table tennis.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In cricket's case, a key difference is the existence of a solid target structure, the wicket (originally, it is thought, a "wicket gate" through which sheep were herded), that the batter must defend.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] It is generally believed that cricket originated as a children's game in the south-eastern counties of England, sometime during the medieval period.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Although there are claims for prior dates, the earliest definite reference to cricket being played comes from evidence given at a court case in Guildford in January 1597 (Old Style, equating to January 1598 in the modern calendar).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Given Derrick's age, it was about half a century earlier when he was at school, and so it is certain that cricket was being played c.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The view that it was originally a children's game is reinforced by Randle Cotgrave's 1611 English-French dictionary in which he defined the noun "*crosse*" as "the crooked staff wherewith boys play at cricket", and the verb form "*crosser*" as "to play at cricket".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] One possible source for the sport's name is the Old English word "*cryce*" (or "*cricc*") meaning a crutch or staff.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In Samuel Johnson's *Dictionary*, he derived cricket from "*cryce*, Saxon, a stick".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In Old French, the word "*criquet*" seems to have meant a kind of club or stick.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Given the strong medieval trade connections between south-east England and the County of Flanders when the latter belonged to the Duchy of Burgundy, the name may have been derived from the Middle Dutch (in use in Flanders at the time) "*krick*"(*-e*), meaning a stick (crook).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Another possible source is the Middle Dutch word "*krickstoel*", meaning a long low stool used for kneeling in church that resembled the long low wicket with two stumps used in early cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] According to Heiner Gillmeister, a European language expert of Bonn University, "cricket" derives from the Middle Dutch phrase for hockey, "*met de (krik ket)sen*" ("with the stick chase").
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Gillmeister has suggested that not only the name but also the sport itself may be of Flemish origin.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Although the main object of the game has always been to score the most runs, the early form of cricket differed from the modern game in certain key technical aspects; the North American variant of cricket known as wicket retained many of these aspects.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The ball was bowled underarm by the bowler and along the ground towards a batter armed with a bat that in shape resembled a hockey stick; the batter defended a low, two-stump wicket; and runs were called notches because the scorers recorded them by notching tally sticks.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1611, the year Cotgrave's dictionary was published, ecclesiastical court records at Sidlesham in Sussex state that two parishioners, Bartholomew Wyatt and Richard Latter, failed to attend church on Easter Sunday because they were playing cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] They were fined 12d each and ordered to do penance.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] This is the earliest mention of adult participation in cricket and it was around the same time that the earliest known organised inter-parish or village match was played, at Chevening, Kent.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1624, a player called Jasper Vinall died after he was accidentally struck on the head during a match between two parish teams in Sussex.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Cricket remained a low-key local pursuit for much of the 17th century.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] It is known, through numerous references found in the records of ecclesiastical court cases, to have been proscribed at times by the Puritans before and during the Commonwealth.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The problem was nearly always the issue of Sunday play, as the Puritans considered cricket to be "profane" if played on the Sabbath, especially if large crowds or gambling were involved.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] According to the social historian Derek Birley, there was a "great upsurge of sport after the Restoration" in 1660.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Several members of the court of King Charles II took a strong interest in cricket during that era.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Gambling on sport became a problem significant enough for Parliament to pass the 1664 Gambling Act, limiting stakes to £100, which was, in any case, a colossal sum exceeding the annual income of 99% of the population.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Along with horse racing, as well as prizefighting and other types of blood sport, cricket was perceived to be a gambling sport.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Rich patrons made matches for high stakes, forming teams in which they engaged the first professional players.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] By the end of the century, cricket had developed into a major sport that was spreading throughout England and was already being taken abroad by English mariners and colonisers—the earliest reference to cricket overseas is dated 1676.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A 1697 newspaper report survives of "a great cricket match" played in Sussex "for fifty guineas apiece", the earliest known contest that is generally considered a First Class match.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The patrons and other players from the gentry began to classify themselves as "amateurs" to establish a clear distinction from the professionals, who were invariably members of the working class, even to the point of having separate changing and dining facilities.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In time, a perception took hold that the typical amateur who played in first-class cricket, until 1962 when amateurism was abolished, was someone with a public school education who had then gone to one of Cambridge or Oxford University.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Society insisted that such people were "officers and gentlemen" whose destiny was to provide leadership.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The game underwent major development in the 18th century to become England's national sport.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Its success was underwritten by the twin necessities of patronage and betting.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Cricket was prominent in London as early as 1707 and, in the middle years of the century, large crowds flocked to matches on the Artillery Ground in Finsbury.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The single wicket form of the sport attracted huge crowds and wagers to match, its popularity peaking in the 1748 season.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Bowling underwent an evolution around 1760 when bowlers began to pitch (bounce) the ball instead of rolling or skimming it towards the batter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] This caused a revolution in bat design because, to deal with the bouncing ball, it was necessary to introduce the modern straight bat in place of the old "hockey stick" shape.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The Hambledon Club was founded in the 1760s and, for the next twenty years until the formation of Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) and the opening of Lord's Old Ground in 1787, Hambledon was both the game's greatest club and its focal point.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] MCC quickly became the sport's premier club and the custodian of the *Laws of Cricket*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] New Laws introduced in the latter part of the 18th century include the three-stump wicket and leg before wicket (lbw).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The 19th century saw underarm bowling superseded by first roundarm and then overarm bowling.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Organisation of the game at county level led to the creation of the county clubs, starting with Sussex in 1839.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In December 1889, the eight leading county clubs formed the official County Championship, which began in 1890.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The most famous player of the 19th century was W.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Grace, who started his long and influential career in 1865.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] It was especially during the career of Grace that the distinction between amateurs and professionals became blurred by the existence of players like him who were nominally amateur but, in terms of their financial gain, *de facto* professional.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Grace himself was said to have been paid more money for playing cricket than any professional.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The last two decades before the First World War have been called the "Golden Age of cricket".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] It is a nostalgic name prompted by the collective sense of loss resulting from the war, but the period did produce some great players and memorable matches, especially as organised competition at county and Test level developed.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Meanwhile, the British Empire had been instrumental in spreading the game overseas, and by the middle of the 19th century it had become well established in Australia, the Caribbean, British India (which also includes present-day Pakistan and Bangladesh), New Zealand, North America and South Africa.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1844, the first international match took place between what were essentially club teams, from the United States and Canada, in New York; Canada won.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1859, a team of English players went to North America on the first overseas tour.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1862, an English team made the first tour of Australia.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The first Australian team to travel overseas consisted of Aboriginal stockmen who toured England in 1868.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1876–77, an England team took part in what was retrospectively recognised as the first-ever Test match at the Melbourne Cricket Ground against Australia.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The rivalry between England and Australia gave birth to The Ashes in 1882, which remains Test cricket's most famous contest.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Test cricket began to expand in 1888–89 when South Africa played England.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The inter-war years were dominated by Australia's Don Bradman, statistically the greatest Test batter of all time.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] To curb his dominance, England employed bodyline tactics during the 1932–33 Ashes series.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] These involved bowling at the body of the batter and setting a field, resulting in batters having to choose between being hit or risk getting out.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] This series moved cricket from a game to a matter of national importance, with diplomatic cables being passed between the two countries over the incident.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] During this time, the number of Test nations continued to grow, with the West Indies, New Zealand and India being admitted as full Test members within a four-year period from 1928 to 1932.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] An enforced break during the Second World War stopped Test Cricket for a time, although the Partition of India caused Pakistan to gain Test status in 1952.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] As teams began to travel more, the game quickly grew from 500 tests in 84 years to 1000 within the next 23.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Cricket entered a new era in 1963 when English counties introduced the limited overs variant.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] As it was sure to produce a result, limited overs cricket was lucrative, and the number of matches increased.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The first Limited Overs International was played in 1971, and the governing International Cricket Council (ICC), seeing its potential, staged the first limited overs Cricket World Cup in 1975.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Meanwhile, South Africa was banned by the ICC due to apartheid from 1970 until 1992.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] 1992 also brought about the introduction of the Zimbabwe team.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The 21st century brought with it the Bangladesh Team, who made their Test debut in 2000.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The game itself also grew, with a new format made up of 20-over innings being created.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] This format, called T20 cricket, quickly became a highly popular format, putting the longer formats at risk.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The new shorter format also introduced franchise cricket, with new tournaments like the Indian Premier League and the Australian Big Bash League.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The ICC has selected the T20 format as cricket's growth format, and has introduced a T20 World Cup which is played every two years; T20 cricket has also been increasingly accepted into major events such as the Asian Games.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The resultant growth has seen cricket's fanbase cross one billion people, with 90% of them in South Asia.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] T20's success has also spawned even shorter formats, such as 10-over cricket (T10) and 100-ball cricket, though not without controversy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Outside factors have also taken their toll on cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] For example, the 2008 Mumbai attacks led India and Pakistan to suspend their bilateral series indefinitely.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The 2009 attack on the Sri Lankan team during their tour of Pakistan led to Pakistan being unable to host matches until 2019.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 2017, Afghanistan and Ireland became the 11th and 12th Test nations.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In cricket, the rules of the game are codified in *The Laws of Cricket* (hereinafter called "the Laws"), which has a global remit.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] There are 42 Laws (always written with a capital "L").
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The earliest known version of the code was drafted in 1744, and since 1788, it has been owned and maintained by its custodian, the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) in London.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Cricket is a bat-and-ball game played on a cricket field (see image of cricket pitch and creases) between two teams of eleven players each.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The field is usually circular or oval in shape, and the edge of the playing area is marked by a boundary, which may be a fence, part of the stands, a rope, a painted line, or a combination of these; the boundary must if possible be marked along its entire length.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In the approximate centre of the field is a rectangular pitch (see image, below) on which a wooden target called a wicket is sited at each end; the wickets are placed 22 yards (20 m) apart.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The pitch is a flat surface 10 feet (3.0 m) wide, with very short grass that tends to be worn away as the game progresses (cricket can also be played on artificial surfaces, notably matting).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Each wicket is made of three wooden stumps topped by two bails.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] As illustrated, the pitch is marked at each end with four white painted lines: a bowling crease, a popping crease and two return creases.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The three stumps are aligned centrally on the bowling crease, which is eight feet eight inches long.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The popping crease is drawn four feet in front of the bowling crease and parallel to it; although it is drawn as a 12 ft (3.7 m) line (six feet on either side of the wicket), it is, in fact, unlimited in length.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The return creases are drawn at right angles to the popping crease so that they intersect the ends of the bowling crease; each return crease is drawn as an 8 ft (2.4 m) line, so that it extends four feet behind the bowling crease, but is also, in fact, unlimited in length.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Before a match begins, the team captains (who are also players) toss a coin to decide which team will bat first and so take the first innings.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] "Innings" is the term used for each phase of play in the match.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In each innings, one team bats, attempting to score runs, while the other team bowls and fields the ball, attempting to restrict the scoring and dismiss the batters.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] When the first innings ends, the teams change roles; there can be two to four innings depending upon the type of match.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A match with four scheduled innings is played over three to five days; a match with two scheduled innings is usually completed in a single day.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] During an innings, all eleven members of the fielding team take the field, but usually only two members of the batting team are on the field at any given time.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The order of batters is usually announced just before the match, but it can be varied.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper (a specialised fielder behind the batter) and the batters wear protective gear because of the hardness of the ball, which can be delivered at speeds of more than 145 kilometres per hour (90 mph) and presents a major health and safety concern.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Protective clothing includes pads (designed to protect the knees and shins), batting gloves or wicket-keeper's gloves for the hands, a safety helmet for the head, and a box for male players inside the trousers (to protect the crotch area).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Some batters wear additional padding inside their shirts and trousers such as thigh pads, arm pads, rib protectors and shoulder pads.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The only fielders allowed to wear protective gear are those in positions very close to the batter (i.e., if they are alongside or in front of him), but they cannot wear gloves or external leg guards.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Subject to certain variations, on-field clothing generally includes a collared shirt with short or long sleeves; long trousers; woolen pullover (if needed); cricket cap (for fielding) or a safety helmet; and spiked shoes or boots to increase traction.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The kit is traditionally all white, and this remains the case in Test and first-class cricket, but in limited overs cricket, team colours are now worn instead.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] White balls are mainly used in limited overs cricket, especially in matches played at night, under floodlights (left). ii) A new red ball.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Red balls are used in day Test cricket, first-class cricket and some other forms of cricket (center).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The essence of the sport is that a bowler delivers (i.e., bowls) the ball from their end of the pitch towards the batter who, armed with a bat, is "on strike" at the other end (see next sub-section: *Basic gameplay*).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The bat is made of wood, usually *Salix alba* (white willow), and has the shape of a blade topped by a cylindrical handle.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The blade must not be more than 4.25 inches (10.8 cm) wide and the total length of the bat not more than 38 inches (97 cm).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] There is no standard for the weight, which is usually between 2 lb 7 oz and 3 lb (1.1 and 1.4 kg).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The ball is a hard leather-seamed spheroid, with a circumference of 9 inches (23 cm).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The ball has a "seam": six rows of stitches attaching the leather shell of the ball to the string and cork interior.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The seam on a new ball is prominent and helps the bowler propel it in a less predictable manner.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] During matches, the quality of the ball deteriorates to a point where it is no longer usable; during the course of this deterioration, its behaviour in flight will change and can influence the outcome of the match.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Players will, therefore, attempt to modify the ball's behaviour by modifying its physical properties.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Polishing the ball and wetting it with sweat or saliva was legal, even when the polishing was deliberately done on one side only to increase the ball's swing through the air.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The use of saliva has since been made illegal due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The acts of rubbing other substances into the ball, scratching the surface or picking at the seams constitute illegal ball tampering.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] During normal play, thirteen players and two umpires are on the field.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Two of the players are batters and the rest are all eleven members of the fielding team.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The other nine players in the batting team are off the field in the pavilion.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The image with overlay below shows what is happening when a ball is being bowled and which of the personnel are on or close to the pitch.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In the photo, the two batters (3 and 8, wearing yellow) have taken position at each end of the pitch (6).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Three members of the fielding team (4, 10 and 11, wearing dark blue) are in shot.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] One of the two umpires (1, wearing white hat) is stationed behind the wicket (2) at the bowler's (4) end of the pitch.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The bowler (4) is bowling the ball (5) from their end of the pitch to the batter (8) at the other end who is called the "striker".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The other batter (3) at the bowling end is called the "non-striker".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper (10), who is a specialist, is positioned behind the striker's wicket (9), and behind them stands one of the fielders in a position called "first slip" (11).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] While the bowler and the first slip are wearing conventional kit only, the two batters and the wicket-keeper are wearing protective gear, including safety helmets, padded gloves and leg guards (pads).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper is the only fielding player able to wear protective gloves.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] While the umpire (1) in shot stands at the bowler's end of the pitch, their colleague stands in the outfield, usually in or near the fielding position called "square leg", so that they are in line with the popping crease (7) at the striker's end of the pitch.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The bowling crease (not numbered) is the one on which the wicket is located between the return creases (12).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The bowler (4) intends to hit the wicket (9) with the ball (5) or at least prevent the striker (8) from scoring runs.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The striker (8) intends, by using their bat, to defend their wicket and, if possible, hit the ball away from the pitch in order to score runs.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Some players are skilled in both batting and bowling, so are termed all-rounders.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Bowlers are classified according to their style and speed, generally as fast bowlers, seam bowlers or spinners.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Batters are classified according to whether they are right-handed or left-handed, with switch-hitting uncommon and largely utilised as a tactic, where a batter changes stance shortly before the bowler releases the ball.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The Laws state that, throughout an innings, "the ball shall be bowled from each end alternately in overs of 6 balls".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The name "over" came about because the umpire calls "Over!" when six legal balls (deliveries) have been bowled.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] At this point, another bowler is deployed at the other end, and the fielding side changes ends while the batters do not.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A bowler cannot bowl two successive overs, although a bowler can (and usually does) bowl alternate overs, from the same end, for several overs which are termed a "spell"; if the captain wants a bowler to "change ends", another bowler must temporarily fill in so that the change is not immediate.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The batters do not change ends at the end of the over, and so the one who was non-striker is now the striker and vice versa.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The umpires also change positions so that the one who was at "square leg" now stands behind the wicket at the nonstriker's end and vice versa.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Of the eleven fielders, three are in shot in the image above.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The other eight are elsewhere on the field, their positions determined on a tactical basis by the captain or the bowler.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Fielders often change position between deliveries, again as directed by the captain or bowler.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If a fielder is injured or becomes ill during a match, a substitute is allowed to field instead of the aforementioned fielder, but the substitute cannot bowl or act as a captain, except in the case of concussion substitutes in international cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The substitute leaves the field when the injured player is fit to return.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The *Laws of Cricket* were updated in 2017 to allow substitutes to act as wicket-keepers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Batters take turns to bat via a batting order which is decided beforehand by the team captain and presented to the umpires, though the order remains flexible when the captain officially nominates the team.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Substitute batters are generally not allowed, except in the case of concussion substitutes in international cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In order to begin batting the batter first adopts a batting stance.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Standardly, this involves adopting a slight crouch with the feet pointing across the front of the wicket, looking in the direction of the bowler, and holding the bat so it passes over the feet and so its tip can rest on the ground near to the toes of the back foot.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A skilled batter can use a wide array of "shots" or "strokes" in both defensive and attacking mode.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The idea is to hit the ball to the best effect with the flat surface of the bat's blade.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the ball touches the side of the bat, it is called an "edge".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The batter does not have to play a shot and can allow the ball to go through to the wicket-keeper.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Equally, the batter does not have to attempt a run when hitting the ball with their bat.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Batters do not always seek to hit the ball as hard as possible, and a good player can score runs by simply making a deft stroke with a turn of the wrists, or by simply "blocking" the ball but directing it away from fielders so that the player has time to take a run.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A wide variety of shots are played, the batter's repertoire including strokes named according to the style of swing and the direction aimed: e.g., "cut", "drive", "hook", and "pull".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Each completed run increments the score of both the team and the striker.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The decision to attempt a run is ideally made by the batter who has the better view of the ball's progress, and this is communicated by calling, usually "yes", "no" or "wait".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] More than one run can be scored from a single hit.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Hits worth one to three runs are common, but the size of the field is such that it is usually difficult to run four or more.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] To compensate for this, hits that reach the boundary of the field are automatically awarded four runs if the ball touches the ground *en route* to the boundary or six runs if the ball clears the boundary without touching the ground within the boundary.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In these cases the batters do not need to run.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Hits for five are unusual and generally rely on the help of "overthrows" by a fielder returning the ball.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If an odd number of runs is scored by the striker, the two batters have changed ends, and the one who was non-striker is now the striker.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Only the striker can score individual runs, but all runs are added to the team's total.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Additional runs can be gained by the batting team as extras (called "sundries" in Australia) due to errors made by the fielding side.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the bowler has bowled an illegal delivery (i.e., a no-ball or a wide), the bowler's team incurs an additional penalty because that ball (i.e., delivery) has to be bowled again, and hence the batting side has the opportunity to score more runs from this extra ball.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In addition, the ways in which the batters can be dismissed on an illegal delivery greatly narrow down; in the case of a no-ball, which is the more egregious type of illegal delivery, the only common way in which the batters can be dismissed is by being run out.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] There are nine ways in which a batter can be dismissed: five relatively common and four extremely rare.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] When a batter is dismissed, they are said to have 'lost their wicket', and are barred from batting again in that inning; their team is also said to have 'lost a wicket'.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Once a team has lost 10 wickets, its innings is over.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Most common dismissals involve the wickets, such as when the ball is bowled at the striker's wicket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The Laws state that the fielding team, usually the bowler in practice, must appeal for a dismissal before the umpire can give their decision.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the batter is out, the umpire raises a forefinger and says "Out!"; otherwise, the umpire will shake their head and say "Not out".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] There is, effectively, a tenth method of dismissal, retired out (self-dismissal – generally permanent except in cases of injury), which is not an on-field dismissal as such but rather a retrospective one for which no fielder is credited.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Most bowlers are considered specialists in that they are selected for the team because of their skill as a bowler, although some are all-rounders, and even specialist batters bowl occasionally.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] These specialists bowl "spells" that are generally 4 to 8 overs long in order not to physically exhaust the bowler, cause muscle strain and stress the skeleton.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The rules prevent a single bowler from bowling consecutive overs, resulting in at least two bowlers alternating each over.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the captain wants a bowler to "change ends", another bowler must temporarily fill in so that the change is not immediate.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The action of bowling the ball is akin to throwing, with the caveat that a bowler's elbow extension is almost entirely restricted, resulting in most bowlers maintaining a straight arm when releasing the ball during their delivery stride.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Additionally, while the bowler is not required to pitch (bounce) the ball, a full toss (non-bouncing) delivery that reaches the striker above waist height is penalised as a no-ball.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A bowler reaches their delivery stride by means of a "run-up", and an over is deemed to have begun when the bowler starts their run-up for the first delivery of that over, the ball then being "in play".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Fast bowlers, or pacemen, need momentum, taking a lengthy run up, while bowlers with a slow delivery take no more than a couple of steps before bowling.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The fastest bowlers can deliver the ball at a speed of over 145 kilometres per hour (90 mph), and they sometimes rely on sheer speed to try to defeat the batter, who is forced to react very quickly.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Other fast bowlers rely on a mixture of speed and guile by making the ball seam or swing (i.e., curve) in flight.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] This type of delivery can deceive a batter into miscuing their shot, for example, so that the ball just touches the edge of the bat and can then be "caught behind" by the wicket-keeper or a slip fielder.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] At the other end of the bowling scale is the spin bowler, who bowls at a relatively slow pace and relies entirely on guile to deceive the batter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A spinner will often "buy their wicket" by "tossing one up" (in a slower, steeper parabolic path) to lure the batter into making a poor shot.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The batter has to be very wary of such deliveries, as the batter is often "flighted" or spun so that the ball will not behave quite as the batter expects it to, and the batter could be "trapped" into getting themself out.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Accidental full toss deliveries can also get wickets, as the failure of the ball to bounce can surprise a batter or induce a poor stroke in an effort to punish the poor delivery with a boundary hit.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In between the pacemen and the spinners are the medium-paced seamers, who rely on persistent accuracy to try to contain the rate of scoring and wear down the batter's concentration.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The captain is often the most experienced player in the team, certainly the most tactically astute, and can possess any of the main skillsets as a batter, a bowler or a wicket-keeper.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Within the Laws, the captain has certain responsibilities in terms of nominating their players to the umpires before the match and ensuring that the captain's players conduct themselves "within the spirit and traditions of the game as well as within the Laws".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper (sometimes called simply the "keeper") is a specialist fielder subject to various rules within the Laws about their equipment and demeanour.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper is the only member of the fielding side who can effect a stumping and is the only one permitted to wear gloves and external leg guards.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Depending on their primary skills, the other ten players in the team tend to be classified as specialist batters or specialist bowlers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Generally, a team will include five or six specialist batters, and four or five specialist bowlers, plus the wicket-keeper.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] There are a number of ways that a cricket match can end and its result be described, depending on whether the team batting first or last wins as well as the format of the game.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the team batting last is 'all out' having scored fewer runs than their opponents, they are said to have "lost by *n* runs" (where *n* is the difference between the aggregate number of runs scored by the teams).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the team that bats last scores enough runs to win, it is said to have "won by *n* wickets", where *n* is the number of wickets left to fall (batters yet to be dismissed) until the team would have been all out.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In a two-innings-a-side match, one team's combined first and second innings total may be less than the other side's first innings total.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The team with the greater score is then said to have "won by an innings and *n* runs" and does not need to bat again: *n* is the difference between the two teams' aggregate scores.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the team batting last is all out and both sides have scored the same number of runs, then the match is a tie; this result is quite rare in matches of two innings a side with only 62 happening in first-class matches from the earliest known instance in 1741 until January 2017.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In the traditional form of the game, if the time allotted for the match expires before either side can win, then the game is declared a draw.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If the match has only a single innings per side, then usually a maximum number of overs applies to each innings.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Such a match is called a "limited overs" or "one-day" match, and the side scoring more runs wins regardless of the number of wickets lost, so that a draw cannot occur.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In some cases, ties are broken by having each team bat for a one-over innings known as a Super Over; subsequent Super Overs may be played if the first Super Over ends in a tie.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] If this kind of match is temporarily interrupted by bad weather, then a complex mathematical formula, known as the Duckworth–Lewis–Stern (DLS) method after its developers, is often used to recalculate a new target score.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A one-day match can also be declared a "no-result" if fewer than a previously agreed number of overs have been bowled by either team, in circumstances that make normal resumption of play impossible, for example, wet weather.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In all forms of cricket, the umpires can abandon the match if bad light or rain makes it impossible to continue.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] There have been instances of entire matches, even Test matches scheduled to be played over five days, being lost to bad weather without a ball being bowled, for example, the third Test of the 1970/71 series in Australia.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The innings (ending with 's' in both singular and plural form) is the term used for each phase of play during a match.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Depending on the type of match being played, each team has either one or two innings.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Sometimes all eleven members of the batting side take a turn to bat but, for various reasons, an innings can end before they have all done so.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The innings terminates if the batting team is "all out", a term defined by the Laws: "At the fall of a wicket or the retirement of a batter, further balls remain to be bowled but no further batter is available to come in".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In this situation, one of the batters has not been dismissed and is termed not out; this is because they have no partners left and there must always be two active batters while the innings is in progress.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The game on the field is regulated by the two umpires, one of whom stands behind the wicket at the bowler's end and the other in a position called "square leg", which is about 15–20 m (49–66 ft) away from the batter on strike and in line with the popping crease on which that umpire is taking guard.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The umpires are authorised to interrupt or even abandon a match due to circumstances likely to endanger the players, such as a damp pitch or deterioration of the light.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Off the field in televised matches, there is usually a third umpire who can make decisions on certain incidents with the aid of video evidence.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The third umpire is mandatory under the playing conditions for Test and Limited Overs International matches played between two ICC full member countries.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] These matches also have a match referee whose job is to ensure that play is within the Laws and the spirit of the game.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The match details, including runs and dismissals, are recorded by two official scorers, one representing each team.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The scorers are directed by the hand signals of an umpire (see image, right).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] For example, the umpire raises a forefinger to signal that the batter is out (has been dismissed); the umpire raises both arms above their head if the batter has hit the ball for six runs.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The scorers are required by the Laws to record all runs scored, wickets taken, and overs bowled; in practice, they also note significant amounts of additional data relating to the game.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] A match's statistics are summarised on a scorecard.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Prior to the popularisation of scorecards, most scoring was done by men sitting on vantage points cuttings notches on tally sticks, and runs were originally called notches.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] According to historian Rowland Bowen, the earliest known scorecard templates were introduced in 1776 by T.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Pratt of Sevenoaks and soon came into general use.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] It is believed that scorecards were printed and sold at Lord's for the first time in 1846.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Scores are displayed differently depending on location, although it is standard to show how many wickets have been lost and how many runs a team has made.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Within Australia, the format is Wickets/Runs, while in the rest of the world, the format is Runs/Wickets.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] For example, a score of 125 runs with 4 wickets lost would be displayed as 4/125 or 125/4, respectively.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Besides observing the Laws, cricketers must respect the "Spirit of Cricket", a concept encompassing sportsmanship, fair play and mutual respect.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] This spirit has long been considered an integral part of the sport but is only nebulously defined.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Amidst concern that the spirit was weakening, in 2000, a Preamble was added to the Laws instructing all participants to play within the spirit of the game.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The Preamble is a short statement intended to emphasise the "positive behaviours that make cricket an exciting game that encourages leadership, friendship, and teamwork".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Its second line states that, "the major responsibility for ensuring fair play rests with the captains, but extends to all players, match officials and, especially in junior cricket, teachers, coaches and parents".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The umpires are the sole judges of fair and unfair play.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] They are required under the Laws to intervene in case of dangerous or unfair play or in cases of unacceptable conduct by a player.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The terse expression of the Spirit of Cricket now avoids trying to enumerate the diverse cultural conventions that exist in the detail of sportsmanship, or its absence.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] Women's cricket was first recorded in Surrey in 1745.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] International development began at the start of the 20th century, and the first Test match was played between Australia and England in December 1934.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The following year, New Zealand joined them, and in 2007 Netherland became the tenth women's Test nation when they made their debut against South Africa.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1958, the International Women's Cricket Council was founded (it merged with the ICC in 2005).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 1973, the first Cricket World Cup of any kind took place when a Women's World Cup was held in England.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In 2005, the International Women's Cricket Council was merged with the International Cricket Council (ICC) to form one unified body to help manage and develop cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] The ICC Women's Rankings were launched on 1 October 2015 covering all three formats of women's cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p01] In October 2018 following the ICC's decision to award T20 International status to all members, the Women's rankings were split into separate ODI (for Full Members) and T20I lists.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The International Cricket Council (ICC), which has its headquarters in Dubai, is the global governing body of cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] It was founded as the Imperial Cricket Conference in 1909 by representatives from England, Australia and South Africa, renamed the International Cricket Conference in 1965 and took up its current name in 1989.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The ICC in 2017 has 105 member nations, twelve of which hold full membership and can play Test cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The ICC is responsible for the organisation and governance of cricket's major international tournaments, notably the men's and women's versions of the Cricket World Cup.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] It also appoints the umpires and referees that officiate at all sanctioned Test matches, Limited Overs Internationals and Twenty20 Internationals.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Each member nation has a national cricket board which regulates cricket matches played in its country, selects the national squad, and organises home and away tours for the national team.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In the West Indies, which for cricket purposes is a federation of nations, these matters are addressed by Cricket West Indies.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Cricket is a multifaceted sport with multiple formats that can effectively be divided into first-class cricket, limited overs cricket, and historically, single wicket cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The highest standard is Test cricket (always written with a capital "T") which is in effect the international version of first-class cricket and is restricted to teams representing the twelve countries that are full members of the ICC (see above).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Although the term "Test match" was not coined until much later, Test cricket is deemed to have begun with two matches between Australia and England in the 1876–77 Australian season; since 1882, most Test series between England and Australia have been played for a trophy known as The Ashes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The term "first-class", in general usage, is applied to top-level domestic cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Test matches are played over five days and first-class over three to four days; in all of these matches, the teams are allotted two innings each and the draw is a valid result.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Limited overs cricket is always scheduled for completion in a single day, and the teams are allotted one innings each.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] There are two main types: List A which normally allows fifty overs per team; and Twenty20 in which the teams have twenty overs each.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Both of the limited overs forms are played internationally as Limited Overs Internationals (LOI) and Twenty20 Internationals (T20I).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] List A was introduced in England in the 1963 season as a knockout cup contested by the first-class county clubs.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In 1969, a national league competition was established.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The concept was gradually introduced to the other leading cricket countries and the first limited overs international was played in 1971.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In 1975, the first Cricket World Cup took place in England.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Twenty20 is a new variant of limited overs itself with the purpose being to complete the match within about three to four hours, usually in an evening session.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The first Twenty20 World Championship was held in 2007.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In addition, a few full-member cricket boards have decided to start leagues that are played in the T10 format, in which games are intended to last approximately 90 minutes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Most recently, in 2021, the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) introduced a new league featuring a hundred-ball tournament, known as The Hundred.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Limited overs matches cannot be drawn, although a tie is possible and an unfinished match is a "no result".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Single wicket was popular in the 18th and 19th centuries, and its matches were generally considered top-class.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In this form, although each team may have from one to six players, there is only one batter in at a time, and that batter must face every delivery bowled while their innings lasts.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Single wicket has rarely been played since limited overs cricket began.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Matches tended to have two innings per team like a full first-class one and they could end in a draw.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Cricket is played at both the international and domestic level.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] There is one major international championship per format, and top-level domestic competitions mirror the three main international formats.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] There are now a number of T20 leagues, which have spawned a "T20 freelancer" phenomenon.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Most international matches are played as parts of 'tours', when one nation travels to another for a number of weeks or months, and plays a number of matches of various sorts against the host nation.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Sometimes a perpetual trophy is awarded to the winner of the Test series, the most famous of which is The Ashes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The ICC also organises competitions that are for several countries at once, including the ICC Men's Cricket World Cup, ICC T20 World Cup and ICC Champions Trophy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] A league competition for Test matches played as part of normal tours, the ICC World Test Championship, had been proposed several times, and its first instance began in 2019.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] A league competition for ODIs, the ICC Cricket World Cup Super League, began in August 2020 and lasted only for one edition.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The ICC maintains Test rankings, ODI rankings and T20 rankings systems for the countries which play these forms of cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Competitions for member nations of the ICC with Associate status include the ICC Intercontinental Cup, for first-class cricket matches, and the World Cricket League for one-day matches, the final matches of which now also serve as the ICC World Cup Qualifier.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The game's only appearance in an Olympic Games was the 1900 Olympics.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] However, it is scheduled to make a return, with the T20 format of the game, in the 2028 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] First-class cricket in England is played for the most part by the 18 county clubs which contest the County Championship.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The concept of a champion county has existed since the 18th century but the official competition was not established until 1890.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The most successful club has been Yorkshire, who had won 32 official titles (plus one shared) as of 2019.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Australia established its national first-class championship in 1892–93 when the Sheffield Shield was introduced.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In Australia, the first-class teams represent the various states.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] New South Wales has the highest number of titles.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The world's earliest known cricket match was a village cricket meeting in Kent which has been deduced from a 1640 court case recording a "cricketing" of "the Weald and the Upland" versus "the Chalk Hill" at Chevening "about thirty years since" (i.e., c.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Inter-parish contests became popular in the first half of the 17th century and continued to develop through the 18th with the first local leagues being founded in the second half of the 19th.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] At the grassroots level, local club cricket is essentially an amateur pastime for those involved but still usually involves teams playing in competitions at weekends or in the evening.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Schools cricket, first known in southern England in the 17th century, has a similar scenario and both are widely played in the countries where cricket is popular.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Although there can be variations in game format, compared with professional cricket, the Laws are always observed and club/school matches are therefore formal and competitive events.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The sport has numerous informal variants such as French cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Cricket has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the Commonwealth of Nations and elsewhere.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] It has, for example, influenced the lexicon of these nations, especially the English language, with various phrases such as "that's not cricket" (that's unfair), "had a good innings" (lived a long life), and "sticky wicket".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] "On a sticky wicket" (*aka* "sticky dog" or "glue pot") is a metaphor used to describe a difficult circumstance.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] It originated as a term for difficult batting conditions in cricket, caused by a damp and soft pitch.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Cricket is the subject of works by noted English poets, including William Blake and Lord Byron.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] *Beyond a Boundary* (1963), written by Trinidadian C.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] James, is often named the best book on any sport ever written.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Francis Bacon, an avid cricket fan, captured a batter in motion.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In music, many calypsos make reference to the Sport of Cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] See List of calypso songs about cricket.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Cricket has close historical ties with Australian rules football and many players have competed at top levels in both sports.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In 1858, prominent Australian cricketer Tom Wills called for the formation of a "foot-ball club" with "a code of laws" to keep cricketers fit during the off-season.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The Melbourne Football Club was founded the following year, and Wills and three other members codified the first laws of the game.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] It is typically played on modified cricket fields.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In England, a number of association football clubs owe their origins to cricketers who sought to play football as a means of keeping fit during the winter months.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Derby County was founded as a branch of the Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1884; Aston Villa (1874) and Everton (1876) were both founded by members of church cricket teams.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] Sheffield United's Bramall Lane ground was, from 1854, the home of the Sheffield Cricket Club, and then of Yorkshire; it was not used for football until 1862 and was shared by Yorkshire and Sheffield United from 1889 to 1973.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] In the late 19th century, a former cricketer, English-born Henry Chadwick of Brooklyn, New York, was credited with devising the baseball box score (which he adapted from the cricket scorecard) for reporting game events.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The first box score appeared in an 1859 issue of the *Clipper*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The statistical record is so central to the game's "historical essence" that Chadwick is sometimes referred to as "the Father of Baseball" because he facilitated the popularity of the sport in its early days.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The influence of cricket and other English sports in British India resulted in the local sports becoming standardised by the 1920s.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/cricket-p02] The 21st century success of the Indian Premier League also inspired the growth of other sports leagues in India, with some of the native sports being further modernised, as with the popular Pro Kabaddi League.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward was crowned at age fourteen after his father was deposed by his mother, Isabella of France, and her lover, Roger Mortimer.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] At age seventeen, he led a successful coup d'état against Mortimer, the *de facto* ruler of England, and began his personal reign.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] After a successful campaign in Scotland, he declared himself rightful heir to the French throne, starting the Hundred Years' War (1337–1453).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Following some initial setbacks, this first phase of the war went exceptionally well for England and would become known as the Edwardian War.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Victories at Crécy and Poitiers led to the highly favourable Treaty of Brétigny (1360), in which England made territorial gains, and Edward renounced his claim to the French throne.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward's later years were marked by foreign policy failure and domestic strife, largely as a result of his decreasing activity and poor health.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The second phase of the Hundred Years' War began in 1369, leading to the loss of most of Edward's conquests, save for the Pale of Calais, by 1375.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward was temperamental and thought himself capable of feats such as healing by the royal touch, as some prior English kings did.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] He was also capable of unusual clemency.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] He was in many ways a conventional medieval king whose main interest was warfare, but he also had a broad range of non-military interests.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Admired in his own time, and for centuries after, he was later denounced as an irresponsible adventurer by Whig historians, but modern historians credit him with significant achievements.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward's father, King Edward II of England had court favourites who were unpopular with his nobility, such as Piers Gaveston and Hugh Despenser the Younger.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Gaveston was killed during a noble rebellion against Edward II in 1312, while Despenser was hated by the English nobility.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward II was also unpopular with the common people due to his repeated demands that they provide unpaid military service in Scotland.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] None of his campaigns there were successful, and this led to a further decline in his popularity, particularly with the nobility.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] His image was damaged again in 1322 when he executed his cousin Thomas, Earl of Lancaster, and confiscated the Lancaster estates.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Historian Chris Given-Wilson wrote that, by 1325, the nobility believed that "no landholder could feel safe" under the regime.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This distrust of Edward II was shared by his wife, Isabella of France, who believed Despenser responsible for poisoning the King's mind against her.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In September 1324 Queen Isabella was publicly humiliated when the government declared her an enemy alien, and the King repossessed her estates, probably at the urging of Despenser.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward II had already been threatened with deposition on two previous occasions (in 1310 and 1321).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Historians agree that hostility towards the king was universal.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Wood ascribed this to Edward II's "cruelty and personal faults", suggesting that "very few, not even his half-brothers or his son, seemed to care about the wretched man" and that none would fight for him.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A contemporary chronicler described Edward II as *rex inutilis*, or a "useless king".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward was born at Windsor Castle on 13 November 1312, and was described in a contemporary prophecy as "the boar that would come out of Windsor".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The reign of his father, Edward II, was a particularly problematic period of English history.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The King had alienated several English nobles and Scottish allies by abandoning his father's war with Scotland soon after his accession, and continued to lose battles against the Scots intermittently.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Also controversial was the King's patronage of a small group of royal favourites rather than his nobility generally.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This, says the historian Michael Prestwich, "unbalanced the whole system of royal patronage".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] However, the birth of a male heir in 1312 – the future Edward III – improved Edward II's relations with the French, and a moderate element within the nobility temporarily quelled baronial opposition.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The young prince was created Earl of Chester at only twelve days old, and by January the following year had been provided with an entire household.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] An early influence on Prince Edward was the Bishop of Durham, Richard de Bury, one of the century's major bibliophiles.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Originally a tutor, he appears to have become a mentor to the King.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Under Bury's tutelage, Edward learned to write and to read French and Latin.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] He would have had access to famous contemporary works, such as Vegetius's *De Re Militari*, which had been translated into Anglo-Norman, as well as the *Mirror for Princes* and various psalters and religious texts.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1325, Edward II was faced with a demand from his brother-in-law Charles IV of France to perform homage for the English Duchy of Aquitaine.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The King was reluctant to leave the country, as discontent was once again brewing domestically, particularly over his relationship with the favourite Hugh Despenser the Younger.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Instead, he had his son Edward created Duke of Aquitaine in his place and sent him to France to perform the homage.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The young Edward was accompanied by his mother Isabella, who was King Charles's sister and was meant to negotiate a peace treaty with the French.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] While in France, Isabella conspired with the exiled Roger Mortimer to have Edward II deposed.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] To build up diplomatic and military support for the venture, Isabella had her son engaged to the twelve-year-old Philippa of Hainault.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] An invasion of England was launched and Edward II's forces deserted him.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Isabella and Mortimer summoned a parliament, and the King was forced to relinquish the throne to his son, who was proclaimed king in London on 25 January 1327.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The new king was crowned as Edward III at Westminster Abbey on 1 February at the age of 14.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] One of Edward's first acts – *de facto* Mortimer's – was to lead another campaign to Scotland in July 1327.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] It was not long before the new reign also met with other problems caused by the central position of Mortimer at court, who was now the de facto ruler of England.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Mortimer used his position to acquire noble estates and titles, and his unpopularity grew with the humiliating defeat by the Scots at the Battle of Stanhope Park in the county of Durham, and the ensuing Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton, agreed with the Scots in 1328.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The young king also came into conflict with his guardian.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Mortimer knew his position in relation to the King was precarious and subjected Edward to disrespect.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The King married Philippa of Hainault at York Minster on 24 January 1328, and the birth of their first child, Edward of Woodstock, on 15 June 1330 only increased tension with Mortimer.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Eventually, the King decided to take direct action against Mortimer.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Although so far Edward had kept a low profile, it is likely that he increasingly suspected that Mortimer's behaviour could endanger Edward's own life, as the former's position became more unpopular.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This was exacerbated by his execution of Edward's uncle Edmund, Earl of Kent.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Contemporary chroniclers suspected, too, that Mortimer had designs on the throne, and it is likely that it was these rumours that encouraged Edward to act against him and his mother, who supposedly maintained a close relationship with Mortimer.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Aided by his close companion William Montagu, 3rd Baron Montagu, and a small number of other trusted men, Edward took Mortimer by surprise and captured him at Nottingham Castle on 19 October 1330.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Mortimer was executed and Edward's personal reign began.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The historian Mark Ormrod argued that at this point Edward had had "little instruction in the art of kingship", and although he had received several books on the subject on his betrothal to Philippa, "it is extremely doubtful that he read or comprehended these works".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] His reign, continues Ormrod, was to be guided by his practical, rather than theoretical, experience.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward III was not content with the peace agreement made in his name, but the renewal of the war with Scotland originated in private, rather than royal initiative.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A group of English magnates known as The Disinherited, who had lost land in Scotland by the peace accord, staged an invasion of Scotland and won a great victory at the Battle of Dupplin Moor in 1332.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] They attempted to install Edward Balliol as king of Scotland in place of the infant David II, but Balliol was soon expelled and was forced to seek the help of Edward III.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The English king responded by laying siege to the important border town of Berwick and defeated a large relieving army at the Battle of Halidon Hill, even while under threat from foreign raids.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] However, Berwick was taken after the besieged Scots set fire to the town, forcing them to treat; at one point Edward's queen was under siege in Bamburgh Castle, but this was too late to save the Scots' campaign.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] He reinstated Balliol on the throne and received a substantial amount of land in southern Scotland.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These victories proved hard to sustain, as forces loyal to David II gradually regained control of the country.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A Scottish uprising in 1334 required the raising of another army and a supporting navy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward, having repaired Roxburgh Castle, launched a number of ineffective strikes against the Scots.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1338, Edward agreed a truce with the Scots.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] One reason for the change of strategy towards Scotland was a growing concern for the relationship between England and France.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] As long as Scotland and France were in an alliance, the English were faced with the prospect of fighting a war on two fronts.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The French carried out raids on English coastal towns, leading to rumours in England of a full-scale French invasion.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] When Edward took power, he found his family in "complete disarray", says Ormrod.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] His nobility was divided into factions after the troublesome reign of his father and was weakened by line failure among many families.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] While the lesser baronage was less affected by political misadventure than their seniors, they were also weaker due to their rights being more insubstantive.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward had to pacify two noble parties: one which had been against his father from the beginning, and another which had opposed Mortimer's and Isabella's minority regime.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] James Bothwell argues that, while he managed to reconcile the sides bloodlessly and with minimum acrimony, it was insufficient to leave him secure on his own: he lanced the opposition but had not turned them into a loyalist cadre.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Only the Earls of Arundel, Oxford and Warwick could be counted on as loyalists.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] To counter the limited loyalty among the aristocrats, following the March 1337 Parliament Edward created six new earls.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] He also summoned 61 new men to the lords with lesser titles, usually by writ of summons, over the rest of his reign.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These creations – although expensive – received very little ill will among the extant aristocracy, including the royal family.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The 1337 creations were Hugh de Audley to the Earldom of Gloucester, William de Bohun to that of Northampton, William de Clinton to Huntingdon, Henry of Grosmont to Derby, William de Montagu to Salisbury and Robert de Ufford to Suffolk.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Of these, Bohun, Clinton, Montagu and Ufford had played leading roles in Edward's coup against Mortimer; they were likewise the greatest beneficiaries in terms of grants and estates.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] James Bothwell has noted that, while these men may have been less well off before they were promoted, they were not less experienced, either politically or militarily.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These promotions were especially important to Edward because it had been from among the earls that his father had created so many bitter enemies, and therefore that was the demography that Edward wanted to reorganise in his favour.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These promotions reinforced his own and the Crown's position and, with war approaching, he created six new recruitment conduits from the regions directly to the royal army.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] For the earls themselves, the prospect was not so positive: due to the parlous state of the royal finances, most of them did not receive a minimum of 1000 marks a year that was promised to them to uphold their new estate.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] All except Gloucester had to be satisfied with irregular grants of land to boost their incomes, but these would often not be available until the incumbent died and they escheated to the King.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1337, Philip VI of France confiscated the English king's Duchy of Aquitaine and the county of Ponthieu.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Instead of seeking a peaceful resolution to the conflict by paying homage to the French king, as his father had done, Edward responded by laying claim to the French crown as the grandson of Philip IV of France.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The French rejected this based on the precedents for agnatic succession set in 1316 and 1322 and upheld the rights of Philip IV's nephew Philip VI, leading to tensions that caused the Hundred Years' War.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In the early stages of the war, Edward's strategy was to build alliances with other Continental rulers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1338, Louis IV, Holy Roman Emperor, named Edward Vicar general of the Holy Roman Empire and promised his support.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] As late as 1373, the Anglo-Portuguese Treaty of 1373 established an Anglo-Portuguese Alliance.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The only major military victory during this phase of the war was the English naval victory at Sluys on 24 June 1340, which secured control of the English Channel.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This victory decimated a superior French fleet and lowered the threat of a French invasion of England, which increased English desires to attack France.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward was unlikely to have been happy with this victory due to his continuing financial problems.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The English also captured 166 French merchantmen; they had been raiding the south coast of England for several years and were unpopular amongst English sailors.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Up to 16,000 French sailors were killed and French captain, Nicolas Béhuchet – who could otherwise have expected to be ransomed – was hanged from his own yardarm.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward saw God's hand in his victory and a triumphal coin was struck in commemoration – showing Edward in a ship, probably meant to be Béhuchet's own – and the King gained a reputation as a naval warrior.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Meanwhile, the fiscal pressure on the kingdom caused by Edward's expensive alliances led to discontent at home.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The regency council at home was frustrated by the mounting national debt, while the King and his commanders on the Continent were angered by the failure of the government in England to provide sufficient funds.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] To deal with the situation, Edward himself returned to England, arriving in London unannounced on 30 November 1340, having given his wife and children as hostages in the Low-Countries to reassure his creditors.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Finding the affairs of the realm in disorder, he purged the royal administration of a great number of ministers and judges.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These measures did not bring domestic stability, and a stand-off ensued between the King and John de Stratford, Archbishop of Canterbury, during which Stratford's relatives Robert Stratford, Bishop of Chichester, and Henry de Stratford were temporarily stripped of title and imprisoned respectively.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Stratford claimed that Edward had violated the laws of the land by arresting royal officers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A certain level of conciliation was reached at the Parliament of April 1341.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Here Edward was forced to accept severe limitations to his financial and administrative freedom, in return for a grant of taxation.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Yet in October the same year, Edward repudiated this statute and Archbishop Stratford was politically ostracised.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The extraordinary circumstances of the April Parliament had forced the King into submission, but under normal circumstances, the powers of the king in medieval England were virtually unlimited, a fact that Edward was able to exploit.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Historian Nicholas Rodger called Edward III's claim to be the "Sovereign of the Seas" into question, arguing there was hardly any royal navy before the reign of Henry V (1413–1422).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Despite Rodger's view, King John had already developed a royal fleet of galleys and had attempted to establish an administration for these ships and others which were arrested (privately owned ships pulled into royal/national service).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Henry III, his successor, continued this work.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Notwithstanding the fact that he, along with his predecessor, had hoped to develop a strong and efficient naval administration, their endeavours produced one that was informal and mostly ad hoc.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A formal naval administration emerged during Edward's reign, comprising lay administrators and led by William de Clewre, Matthew de Torksey and John de Haytfield successively bearing the title of *Clerk of the King's Ships*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Robert de Crull was the last to fill this position during Edward III's reign and would have the longest tenure in this position.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] It was during his tenure that Edward's naval administration would become a base for what evolved during the reigns of successors such as Henry VIII's *Council of Marine* and *Navy Board* and Charles I's *Board of Admiralty*.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Rodger also argues that for much of the fourteenth century, the French had the upper hand, apart from Sluys in 1340 and, perhaps, off Winchelsea in 1350.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Yet, the French never invaded England and King John II of France died in captivity in England.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] There was a need for an English navy to play a role in this and to handle other matters, such as the insurrection of the Anglo-Irish lords and acts of piracy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward's military command structure began with himself at the centre, and then members of the court acted as his generals.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This included the King's family, and Edward utilised the martial capabilities of his sons, particularly his eldest son, Edward the Black Prince.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This was not only pragmatic, in that they were all good warriors, but had the added propaganda value of demonstrating the hereditary nature of Edward's claim to the French throne.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] However, command was not always the prerogative of the nobility.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Knights Banneret – knights able to lead other knights – were also favoured as leaders of armies or divisions, as they were also already close to the king, being part of his household and bodyguard.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] They bore particular responsibilities during King Edward's *chevauchées*, which often required the main army to split into smaller forces, each requiring its own captain.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] For example, in the 1369 Loire campaign, the Earl of Pembroke shared command with Sir John Chandos; although the latter was appointed seneschal of France by the Black Prince, Pembroke refused to work beneath him on account of his superior social status.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Ultimately, though, the task of raising the armies that they would lead fell to both: the aristocracy could raise the largest number of tenants and retainers after the King, but it was the lower men who acted as recruiting sergeants in the regions.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Unlike during his father's or great-grandfather's campaigns in Scotland, the feudal levy ― whereby military service was provided for free in exchange for land rights ― by the outbreak of the Hundred Years' War it had become the norm for men of all ranks to be paid for their service from the King.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In return, the crown shouldered the responsibility for paying for the bulk of equipment.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The military historian Andrew Ayton has described this transition as amounting to a "military revolution", and one spearheaded by the King himself.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] By the early 1340s, it was clear that Edward's policy of alliances was too costly, and yielded too few results.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The following years saw more direct involvement by English armies, including in the Breton War of Succession, but these interventions also proved fruitless at first.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward defaulted on large scale Florentine loans, and partly as a result the lenders declared bankruptcy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A change came in July 1346, when Edward staged a major offensive, sailing for Normandy with a force of 15,000 men.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] His army sacked the city of Caen, and marched across northern France, to meet up with Flemish forces in Flanders.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] It was not Edward's initial intention to engage the French army, but at Crécy, just north of the Somme, he found favourable terrain and decided to fight a pursuing army led by Philip VI.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] On 26 August, the English army defeated a far larger French army in the Battle of Crécy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Shortly after this, on 17 October, an English army defeated and captured King David II of Scotland at the Battle of Neville's Cross.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] With his northern borders secured, Edward felt free to continue his major offensive against France, laying siege to the town of Calais.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The operation was the greatest English venture of the Hundred Years' War, involving an army of 32,000 men.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The siege started on 4 September 1346, and lasted until the town surrendered on 3 August 1347.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] After the fall of Calais, factors outside of Edward's control forced him to wind down the war effort.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1348, the Black Death struck England with full force, killing a third or more of the country's population.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This loss of manpower led to a shortage of farm labour and a corresponding rise in wages.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The great landowners struggled with the shortage of manpower and the resulting inflation in labour cost.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] To curb the rise in wages, the King and Parliament responded with the Ordinance of Labourers in 1349, followed by the Statute of Labourers in 1351.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These attempts to regulate wages could not succeed in the long run, but in the short term they were enforced with great vigour.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] All in all, the plague did not lead to a full-scale breakdown of government and society, and recovery was remarkably swift.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This was to a large extent thanks to the competent leadership of royal administrators such as Treasurer William Edington and Chief Justice William de Shareshull.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] It was not until the mid-1350s that military operations on the Continent were resumed on a large scale.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1356, Edward's eldest son, Edward, Prince of Wales, won an important victory in the Battle of Poitiers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The greatly outnumbered English forces not only routed the French, but captured the French king John II and his youngest son, Philip.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] After a succession of victories, the English held great possessions in France, the French king was in English custody, and the French central government had almost totally collapsed.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] There has been a historical debate as to whether Edward's claim to the French crown originally was genuine, or if it was simply a political ploy meant to put pressure on the French government.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Regardless of the original intent, the stated claim now seemed to be within reach.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Yet a campaign in 1359, meant to complete the undertaking, was inconclusive.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1360, therefore, Edward accepted the Treaty of Brétigny, whereby he renounced his claims to the French throne, but secured his extended French possessions in full sovereignty.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward kept his subjects fully informed of political and military developments abroad by a large number of regular reports from himself and his captains to various outlets, including convocation, the City of London and the archbishops, that, while the scholar A.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Prince acknowledged that taken singularly, these reports may not represent a cohesive public relations within government, they do perhaps indicate, as a whole, the existence of a "simple propaganda organization" with which the King boosted domestic morale.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These then ended up as part of popular chronicles, either verbatim or in part, whether newsletters or public letters.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The middle years of Edward's reign were a period of significant legislative activity.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Perhaps the best-known piece of legislation passed was the Statute of Labourers of 1351, which addressed the labour shortage problem caused by the Black Death.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The statute fixed wages at their pre-plague level and checked peasant mobility by asserting that lords had the first claim on their men's services.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In spite of concerted efforts to uphold the statute, it eventually failed due to intense competition among landowners for labour.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The law has been described as an attempt "to legislate against the law of supply and demand", which doomed it to certain failure.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Nevertheless, the labour shortage had created a community of interest between the smaller landowners of the House of Commons and the greater landowners of the House of Lords.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The resulting measures angered the peasants, leading to the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The reign of Edward III coincided with the so-called Babylonian Captivity of the papacy at Avignon.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] During the wars with France, opposition emerged in England against perceived injustices by a papacy largely controlled by the French crown.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Papal taxation of the English Church was suspected to be financing the nation's enemies, while the practice of provisions (the Pope's providing benefices for clerics) caused resentment in the English population.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The statutes of Provisors and Praemunire, of 1350 and 1353 respectively, aimed to amend this by banning papal benefices, as well as limiting the power of the papal court over English subjects.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The statutes did not sever the ties between the king and the Pope, who were equally dependent upon each other.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Other legislation of importance includes the Treason Act 1351.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] It was precisely the harmony of the reign that allowed a consensus on the definition of this controversial crime.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Yet, the most significant legal reform was probably that concerning the Justices of the Peace.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This institution began before the reign of Edward III but, by 1350, the justices had been given the power not only to investigate crimes and make arrests, but also to try cases, including those of felony.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] With this, an enduring fixture in the administration of local English justice had been established.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Parliament as a representative institution was already well established by the time of Edward III, but the reign was nevertheless central to its development.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] During this period, membership in the English baronage, formerly a somewhat indistinct group, became restricted to those who received a personal summons to Parliament.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This happened as Parliament gradually developed into a bicameral institution, composed of a House of Lords and a House of Commons.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Yet it was not in the Lords, but in the Commons that the greatest changes took place, with the expanding political role of the Commons.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Informative is the Good Parliament, where the Commons for the first time – albeit with noble support – were responsible for precipitating a political crisis.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In the process, both the procedure of impeachment and the office of the Speaker were created.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Even though the political gains were of only temporary duration, this parliament represented a watershed in English political history.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The political influence of the Commons originally lay in their right to grant taxes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The financial demands of the Hundred Years' War were enormous, and the King and his ministers tried different methods of covering the expenses.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward had a steady income from crown lands, and could also take up substantial loans from Italian and domestic financiers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] To finance warfare, he had to resort to taxation of his subjects.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Taxation took two primary forms: levy and customs.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The levy was a grant of a proportion of all moveable property, normally a tenth for towns and a fifteenth for farmland.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This could produce large sums of money, but each such levy had to be approved by Parliament, and the king had to prove the necessity.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The customs therefore provided a welcome supplement, as a steady and reliable source of income.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] An "ancient duty" on the export of wool had existed since 1275.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward I had tried to introduce an additional duty on wool, but this unpopular *maltolt*, or "unjust exaction", was soon abandoned.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Then, from 1336 onwards, a series of schemes aimed at increasing royal revenues from wool export were introduced.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] After some initial problems and discontent, it was agreed through the Statute of the Staple of 1353 that the new customs should be approved by Parliament, though in reality, they became permanent.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Through the steady taxation of Edward III's reign, Parliament – and in particular the Commons – gained political influence.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A consensus emerged that in order for a tax to be just, the King had to prove its necessity, it had to be granted by the community of the realm, and it had to be to the benefit of that community.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In addition to imposing taxes, Parliament would also present petitions for redress of grievances to the King, most often concerning misgovernment by royal officials.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This way the system was beneficial for both parties.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Through this process, the Commons, and the community they represented, became increasingly politically aware, and the foundation was laid for the particular English brand of constitutional monarchy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] It became the norm for the king's ministers to argue his case before Parliament, the Commons to grant the king the tax he requested, and then the king's concessions to Parliament would be announced at its end.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The King occasionally attempted to avoid resorting to Parliament to raise taxes, such as in 1338 when he attempted a forced loan on wool.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This soon collapsed – in the words of E.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Fryde it was a "lamentable failure" – and once again, Edward had to return to Parliament.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward also attempted to reinforce what he believed to be his ancient rights, such as the return of all goods and chattels of felons to the Crown, and scutage, as well as new proposals, such as that debts should be repaid to the Crown in one payment rather than incrementally.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] All these schemes collapsed, however, the latter because the lords claimed that such a method of taxation infringed upon their traditional rights.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] According to Fryde, "one of Edward's most onerous and wasteful liabilities" came in February 1339, when he effectively pawned the Great Crown of England to the Archbishop of Trier, for which the King promised repayment of £16,650.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward met his creditors in Ghent in 1340, but, unable to immediately satisfy their demands, notes Bertie Wilkinson, "pretending that he wanted to take a walk, he secretly rode away".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Furthermore, Edward bolstered the sense of community within this group by the creation of a new order of chivalry.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In January 1344 a great feast was held in Windsor Castle to which large numbers were invited; not just the lords but the City of London also sent a contingent.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The first night saw a feast at which all the attending ladies, with only two knights among them, dined, while the other men ate in their tents.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This was followed by jousting over the next three days, where Edward – "not because of his kingly rank but because of his great exertions", Adam Murimuth claims in his chronicle – was deemed champion.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This was followed by the King's announcement of the founding of the Round Table of King Arthur, to which "certain lords" took an oath.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The first meeting of the new chapter was arranged for the following Whitsun.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Nothing, however, was to come of the project; as Murimuth comments, "this work was later stopped for various reasons".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Instead, around four years later, Edward founded the Order of the Garter, probably in 1348.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The new order carried connotations from the legend by the circular shape of the garter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward's wartime experiences during the Crécy campaign (1346–7) seem to have been a determining factor in his abandonment of the Round Table project.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] It has been argued that the total warfare tactics employed by the English at Crécy in 1346 were contrary to Arthurian ideals and made Arthur a problematic paradigm for Edward, especially at the time of the institution of the Garter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] There are no formal references to King Arthur and the Round Table in the surviving early fifteenth century copies of the Statutes of the Garter, but the Garter Feast of 1358 did involve a round table game.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Thus, there was some overlap between the projected Round Table fellowship and the actualized Order of the Garter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Polydore Vergil tells of how the young Joan of Kent – allegedly the King's favourite at the time – accidentally dropped her garter at a ball at Calais.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward responded to the ensuing ridicule of the crowd by tying the garter around his own knee with the words *honi soit qui mal y pense* (shame on him who thinks ill of it).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This reinforcement of the aristocracy and the emerging sense of an English national identity must be seen in conjunction with the war in France.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Just as the war with Scotland had done, the fear of a French invasion helped strengthen a sense of national unity and nationalise the aristocracy that had been largely Anglo-Norman since the Norman Conquest.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Since the time of Edward I, popular myth suggested that the French planned to extinguish the English language, and as his grandfather had done, Edward III made the most of this scare.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] As a result, the English language experienced a strong revival during Edward III's reign; in 1362, a Statute of Pleading ordered English to be used in law courts, and the year after, Parliament was for the first time opened in English.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] At the same time, the vernacular saw a revival as a literary language, through the works of William Langland, John Gower and especially *The Canterbury Tales* by Geoffrey Chaucer.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Yet the extent of this Anglicisation must not be exaggerated.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The statute of 1362 was in fact written in the French language and had little immediate effect, and Parliament was opened in that language as late as 1377.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The Order of the Garter, though a distinctly English institution, included also foreign members such as John IV, Duke of Brittany, and Robert of Namur.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] While Edward's early reign had been energetic and successful, his later years were marked by inertia, military failure and political strife.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The day-to-day affairs of the state had less appeal to Edward than military campaigning, so during the 1360s Edward increasingly relied on the help of his subordinates, in particular William Wykeham.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] A relative upstart, Wykeham was made Keeper of the Privy Seal in 1363 and Chancellor in 1367, though due to political difficulties connected with his inexperience, the Parliament forced him to resign the chancellorship in 1371.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Compounding Edward's difficulties were the deaths of his most trusted men, some from the 1361–62 recurrence of the plague.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] William Montagu, 1st Earl of Salisbury, Edward's companion in the 1330 coup, died as early as 1344.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] William de Clinton, 1st Earl of Huntingdon, who had also been with Edward at Nottingham, died in 1354.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] One of the earls created in 1337, William de Bohun, 1st Earl of Northampton, died in 1360, and the next year Henry of Grosmont, Duke of Lancaster, perhaps the greatest of Edward's captains, succumbed to what was probably plague.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Their deaths left the majority of the magnates younger and more naturally aligned to the princes than to the King himself.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Increasingly, Edward began to rely on his sons for the leadership of military operations.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The king's second son, Lionel of Antwerp, attempted to subdue by force the largely autonomous Anglo-Irish lords in Ireland.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The venture failed, and the only lasting mark he left was the suppressive Statutes of Kilkenny in 1366.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In France, meanwhile, the decade following the Treaty of Brétigny was one of relative tranquillity, but on 8 April 1364, John II died in captivity in England, after unsuccessfully trying to raise his own ransom at home.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] He was followed by the vigorous Charles V, who enlisted the help of the capable Bertrand du Guesclin, Constable of France In 1369, the French war started anew, and Edward's son John of Gaunt was given the responsibility of a military campaign.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The effort failed, and with the Treaty of Bruges in 1375, the great English possessions in France were reduced to only the coastal towns of Calais, Bordeaux, and Bayonne.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Alice Perrers was originally one of Philippa's household ladies, having been appointed by 1359.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Within five years, by which time she would have been 18, and after the death of her husband, she is speculated to have become the lover of the elderly King.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] She maintained an active business life outside her career in the royal household, particularly as a moneylender, while also making the most out of her royal connections, accepted gifts from courtiers and those wishing to further their causes with the King.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward presented her with gifts, including land, manors and jewels, and in 1371 these included those of the now-dead Philippa.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Alice, in what may have been an attempt to keep her new estates after the King's death, tied them up in a series of enfeoffments.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] This meant that legally they ceased to be royal gifts which could be resumed to the Crown, but hers to receive from her feoffees when she chose.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] These gifts included 50 manors in 25 counties and £20,000 in jewels.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Another contemporary, the Anonimalle Chronicler, complained that this was all "without any notable profit and in great damage to our lord the king", and urged that Alice be removed from the King's circle even though he was still living, albeit known to be dying.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Modern historians have credited her with more agency than merely using "womanly wiles" to get her own way, noting her head for business and the law.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward could not prevent her banishment during the Good Parliament, though she had returned to his inner circle later that year and remained there until his death.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] However, in 1378 (first year of Richard II's reign) she was put on trial before Parliament.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] She was found guilty and sentenced to exile.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Further, her property was forfeited to the Crown.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Military failure abroad, and the associated fiscal pressure of constant campaigns, led to political discontent in England.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Finance was a particular grievance; although it was rarely raised as an issue before 1371, after that time complaints about the royal household's expenditure were frequent.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The problems came to a head in the Parliament of 1376, the so-called Good Parliament.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The Parliament was called to grant taxation, but the House of Commons took the opportunity to address specific grievances.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In particular, criticism was directed at some of the King's closest advisors.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Lord Chamberlain William Latimer, 4th Baron Latimer, and Steward of the Household John Neville, 3rd Baron Neville de Raby, were dismissed from their positions.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward III's mistress, Alice Perrers, who was seen to hold far too much power over the ageing king, was banished from court.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Yet the real adversary of the Commons, supported by powerful men such as Wykeham and Edmund Mortimer, 3rd Earl of March, was John of Gaunt.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Both the King and Edward of Woodstock were by this time incapacitated by illness, leaving Gaunt in virtual control of government.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Gaunt was forced to give in to the demands of Parliament, but at its next convocation in 1377, most of the achievements of the Good Parliament were reversed and a poll tax was instituted to pay for the war.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward III did not have much to do with any of this; after around 1375 he played a limited role in the government of the realm.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Around 29 September 1376, he fell ill with a large abscess.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] After a brief period of recovery in February 1377, the King died of a stroke at Sheen on 21 June.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Edward III was succeeded by his ten-year-old grandson, King Richard II, son of Edward of Woodstock, since Woodstock himself had died on 8 June 1376.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] In 1376, Edward had signed letters patent on the order of succession to the crown, citing in second position his third son John of Gaunt, but ignoring Philippa, daughter of his second son Lionel of Antwerp, Duke of Clarence.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] Philippa's exclusion contrasted with a decision by Edward I in 1290, which had recognized the right of women to inherit the crown and to pass it on to their descendants.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The order of succession determined in 1376 led the House of Lancaster to the throne in 1399 (Gaunt was Duke of Lancaster), whereas the rule decided by Edward I would have favoured Philippa's descendants, among them the House of York, beginning with Richard of York, her great-grandson.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p01] The large number of cousins that were created is sometimes argued to have laid the foundations for the Wars of the Roses in the fifteenth century.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward III and his wife Philippa had seven sons and five daughters born over a 25-year period.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] This was considered a success by contemporaries and a sign of God's favour.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward understood the importance of a "strong and united royal family", argues Ormrod.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] It allowed him, through their marriages, to make alliances within his own aristocracy and also with continental dynasties.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] However, the latter policy gradually fell apart with the gradual loss of England's European possessions towards the end of the century.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] For example, he organised the marriage of his sister Eleanor of Woodstock to the Count of Guelders as part of a pro-Netherlandish, anti-French policy in 1332.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Yet when the coalition collapsed in 1340, the fact that he had only lost her in that particular marriage market was a positive.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] From around this time, says Ormrod, "the Hundred Years' War became a family enterprise": Edward the Black Prince commanded a force at Crécy, and ten years later his younger brothers Lionel, John and Edmund had joined the war.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] However, while his sons were fighting in France, they could not be procreating the royal line; by 1358, only Lionel had married and provided Edward with a grandchild.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] By the mid-1360s his family had furthered his continental policy, both diplomatically and militarily, sufficiently that he allowed his son Edward and his daughter Isabella to do that rarest of things in the Middle Ages: marry for love.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Neither the former's match with Joan of Kent and the latter's to Enguerrand VII de Coucy, were particularly advantageous to the King; the first was a clandestine marriage, while de Courcy was a French hostage.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] A fourth son, Thomas of Windsor, is also sometimes posited as being born in 1347 and dying the following year.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] However, the historian Kathryn Warner has suggested that, as William of Woodstock was also born and died the same year, and combined with the paucity of material evidence, it is likely that this Thomas is a composite.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] She argues that "the entire existence of 'Thomas of Windsor' in some modern books and websites appears to be based on the spurious story by two chroniclers that Philippa was heavily pregnant when she interceded for the Calais burghers in early August 1347".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] She also notes that for William, who also died young, there is much evidence for his existence, including "his funeral or tomb, or for the queen's purification after his birth, or for any kind of celebration held to mark the birth of another royal child".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] The medievalist Nicholas Orme has noted that medieval chroniclers were particularly accurate when it came to recording royal births.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] The geneticist Adam Rutherford has calculated Edward had over 300 great-great-grandchildren and, therefore, over 20,000 descendants by 1600.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Thus, by the 21st century, it is "virtually impossible" that a person with a predominantly British ancestry is not descended from Edward III, as they would have around 32,000 ancestors from 1600.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Rutherford has calculated that statistically, the odds on a 20th-century British person not being descended from Edward III is 0.99532,768 = 4.64 × 10−72.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Mark Ormrod has noted that in this period, politics was often dictated by the personality and character of the king.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] However, it was also understood that not only should a king rule well and wisely, but that he should be seen to do so.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Ormrod argues that, while Edward III did not begin his reign with these skills, unlike many of his fellow Plantagenet kings, he acquired them.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] His collection of chronicles indicates an interest in history, even to the extent that, on occasion, he consulted their authors.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] He may have been particularly keen to emulate Henry II and Edward I, whose own martial prowess and success would have resonated with him.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] His tastes were conventional, Ormrod says, and J.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Lander also has argued that this is reflected in his hobbies.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Unlike his father's passion for manual work, including carpentry, thatching and rowing, Edward III "shared to the full the conventional tastes and pleasure of the aristocracy", with his principal interest being architecture.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] This conservativism is reflected in his religious views, which, expressed as they were through the patronage of friaries and visiting of shrines, demonstrate a conventional religion.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] This is also reflected in his almsgiving.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] While ancestors such as Henry III had often been haphazard and exuberant in the amounts they gave and when they did so, Edward III maintained a regular 366 meals a week to be provided for the poor with another £25 to be distributed during the four main feasts.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] However, alongside his conventionality ran a populist streak, and Ormrod has described him as a "natural showman", particularly in his alacrity to heal those suffering from scrofula by his royal touch.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] In less than two years, between 1338 and 1340, he touched for scrofula in both England and while campaigning in France; another 355 occurred between November 1340 and the same month the following year.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] He was generous to the point of extravagance.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] In an alternative view, Norman Cantor has described Edward as an "avaricious and sadistic thug".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] From what is known of Edward's character, he could be impulsive and temperamental, as was seen by his actions against Stratford and the ministers in 1340/41.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Other escapades were not just impulsive but dangerous, such as in 1349, when he sailed to Calais with only a small bodyguard.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] At the same time, he was well known for his clemency; Mortimer's grandson was not only absolved, he came to play an important part in the French wars and was eventually made a Knight of the Garter.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] His favourite pursuit was the art of war and, in this, he conformed to the medieval notion of good kingship.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] As a warrior he was so successful that one modern military historian has described him as the greatest general in English history.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] He seems to have been unusually devoted to Queen Philippa.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Much has been made of Edward's sexual licentiousness, but there is no evidence of any infidelity on his part before Alice Perrers became his lover, and by that time the Queen was already terminally ill.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] This devotion extended to the rest of the family as well; in contrast to many of his predecessors, Edward never experienced opposition from any of his five adult sons.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward III, argues the scholar Michael A.R.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] These were the large brood of children and grandchildren he left, and his claim to the French throne.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Secondly, while the resumption of Edward's claims and war in France was initially successful—contemporaries compared Henry V's decisive victory at Agincourt with Edward's at Crécy and Poitiers—when the tide turned against the English in France, the dynasty was also weakened.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Indeed, war in France was problematic for the House of York as well as Lancaster.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward IV was probably consciously following in his namesake's footsteps when he invaded France in 1475, even if the subsequent Treaty of Picquigny was wholly unintended.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward IV's reign looked back on that of Edward III – with its martial and administrative progress – as something to model their own on, argues Morgan.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward IV's own *Household Books*, summarise the approach as "we take to bylde upon a more perfit new house", and indeed many of their grants and warrants contain a final clause that whatever was under discussion should be as they were in Edward III's final year.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Even the final destruction of the Plantagenets at Bosworth in 1485 failed to impinge on Edward III's posthumous image; he was also the most recent king Henry VII could lay claim of descent from.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward III enjoyed unprecedented popularity in his own lifetime, and even the troubles of his later reign were never blamed directly on the King himself.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] His contemporary Jean Froissart wrote in his *Chronicles*: "His like had not been seen since the days of King Arthur." D.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] This view persisted for a while but, with time, Edward's image changed.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] The Whig historians of a later age preferred constitutional reform to foreign conquest and accused Edward of ignoring his responsibilities to his own nation.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Later scholarship, suggests Ormrod, "tended to be rather kinder".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] In a 1960 article, May McKisack points out the teleological nature of Stubbs' judgement.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] A medieval king could not be expected to work towards some future ideal of a parliamentary monarchy as if it were good in itself; rather, his role was a pragmatic one – to maintain order and solve problems as they arose.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward had also been accused of endowing his younger sons too liberally and thereby promoting dynastic strife culminating in the Wars of the Roses.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] McFarlane, who argued that this was not only the common policy of the age, but also the best.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Later biographers of Edward such as Mark Ormrod and Ian Mortimer have followed this historiographical trend.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] The older negative view has not completely disappeared; Cantor has argued that Edward was a "destructive and merciless force".
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Ormrod argues that in overturning the Stubbsian paradigm, historians may have gone too far in the opposite direction, not taking into account the problems he had to solve and the number of different factions he had to accommodate to get things done.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Chris Given-Wilson and Michael Prestwich, in their introduction to the proceedings of the 1999 Centre for Medieval Studies conference at the University of York, summarise modern consensus as being, effectively, that he was, overall, a strong king, a just king and a good warrior and strategist.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] This, they argue, is the most important point regarding modern scholarship on Edward III: not necessarily to overturn previous consensus, but to look at all aspects of a multi-faceted King and examine how he achieved this success.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Modern historians are also more distant than contemporaries in their view of the King's fecundity being a sign of success; more often, it is seen as a liability as each mouth had to be paid for, draining limited resources.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Further, it may have led to later partisanship between the Crown and its cadet branches.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Edward's grandson, the young Richard II, faced political and economic problems, many resulting from the Black Death, including the Peasants' Revolt that broke out across the south of England in 1381.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Over the coming decades, Richard and groups of nobles vied for power and control of policy towards France until Henry of Bolingbroke seized the throne with the support of Parliament in 1399.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Ruling as Henry IV, he exercised power through a royal council and Parliament, while attempting to enforce political and religious conformity.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] His son, Henry V, reinvigorated the war with France and came close to achieving strategic success shortly before his death in 1422.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] Henry VI became king at the age of only nine months and both the English political system and the military situation in France began to unravel.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] A sequence of bloody civil wars – later termed the Wars of the Roses – erupted in 1455, spurred on by an economic crisis and a widespread perception of poor government.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/edward-iii-p02] The idea that Edward III was to blame for the later-15th century Wars of the Roses was prevalent as late as the 19th century, but came to be challenged in the 20th.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] After studying and working in continental Europe, Forbes settled in Newlyn, England, where she raised her son and established a school with her husband, Stanhope Forbes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She had her works exhibited in notable shows and won medals for her works.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Her paintings are in collections of museums in Canada, United States and England.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Armstrong was born 29 December 1859 in Kingston, Canada West.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She was the youngest child of William Armstrong, an employee of the government of the United Province of Canada.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Born in her father's old age, she was educated privately in Canada and then allowed to further her artistic studies in England with her mother as chaperone.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Her father died two months later, after which she and her mother lived with an uncle in Chelsea, London.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] They lived next door to Dante Gabriel Rossetti, but she never met him.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In 1889, she married Newlyn School painter Stanhope Forbes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In 1904, she and her husband settled at Higher Faugan, a house which they designed and had built for themselves.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In 1909, she pursued cures and restorative periods for cancer in France and London, but died in 1912.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In an obituary, she was dubbed "the Queen of Newlyn" for her contributions to the art colony.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Her husband remarried following her death.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] As a young girl, Elizabeth Armstrong, later Forbes, traveled with her mother to England and studied at the South Kensington Art School (now the Royal College of Art).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She then returned to Canada, during which time her father died.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] From 1877 to 1880 she studied at the Art Students League of New York with William Merritt Chase, who recommended that she next study in Munich.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Following his advice, Armstrong went to Germany and studied with J.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Frank Currier and Frank Duveneck in the early 1880s.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In 1882, she explored plein air painting at the artists' colony at Pont-Aven in Brittany.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] While in Brittany, she sent paintings to London for sale at the Royal Institute and all of the items that she sent were sold on the opening day of the show.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] The following year, she was in London, where she worked as a print maker and joined the Society of Painter Etchers.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In the summer of 1884 she studied near Haarlem in Zandvoort, the Netherlands with William Merritt Chase.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She worked in oil, watercolour and pastels and made etchings of children, landscapes and fishing scenes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Her works were exhibited in London at the Royal Institute of Painters in Water Colours and the Royal Academy.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Some of her etchings, influenced by James Abbott McNeill Whistler and Walter Sickert, were collected by her Pont-Aven mentor, Mortimer Menpes.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In the autumn of 1885, Armstrong and her mother moved to Newlyn, Cornwall.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She established a studio in Newlyn, sharing the building with a fisherman who stored and repaired nets in the space.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She won a medal at the Paris International Exhibition in 1891 and a gold medal for an oil painting at the World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago in 1893.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Between 1893 and 1899 she participated in more than 63 exhibitions in London.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Ives, where she met Stanhope Forbes, whom she married in 1889.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Going against societal roles for married women, Elizabeth Forbes continued to be an active and successful artist after marriage.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Further, in 1899 she and her husband opened the Newlyn Art School.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] They were instrumental in the creation and ongoing success of the new Passmore Edwards Art Gallery at Newlyn, also known as the Newlyn Art Gallery (NAG).
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Her works of art, many of them of children, including her son Alec, were influenced by French realism.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She was a successful artist, more successful than some of her male counterparts, and had a national reputation, most commonly associated with the Newlyn School, or Forbes School.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Forbes held an exhibition called *Children and Child Lore* in London at the Fine Art Society in 1900.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] The main character based upon her friend Thomas Cooper Gotch, Forbes wrote and illustrated *King Arthur's Wood*, a children's book for her son that was published in 1904.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] She founded *The Paper Chase*, edited by her friend F.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Tennyson Jesse in 1908, and wrote poetry.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] In 1910, at the Royal British Colonial Society of Artists Exhibition, Forbes won the merit award.
[src:albert-chevallier-tayler/elizabeth-forbes-artist] Her works are exhibited at National Gallery of Canada, National Museum of Women in the Arts in Washington, D.C., Royal Cornwall Museum, Penlee House, Victoria and Albert Museum, West Cornwall Art Archive and in museums in Liverpool, London and Manchester.
